{[%evp 0,6,16,16,66,50,95,65,65]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nc6 {In this line,
the Rossolimo meets the Moscow Variation since it can also arise via the move
order 2...Nc6 3.Bb5 d6. In lesson one, we will look at typical ideas and
disregard the theory for the moment. Firstly, we will study the "Spanish"
approach - i.e. Black is playing . ..e5 at some point. Secondly, we will see a
number of typical mistakes on Black's part and the way to punish them. We will
study the main continuation 4. 0-0 Bd7 in some detail, both from the strategic
and theoretical points of view.} *

[Event "ch-POL Rapid 2017"]
[Site "Zgierz POL"]
[Date "2017.01.08"]
[Round "8.15"]
[White "Bartel, Mi"]
[Black "Krzywda, A."]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "B51"]
[WhiteElo "2380"]
[BlackElo "2148"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "73"]
[EventDate "2017.01.08"]

{I encourage you to study this very instructive game (and the included
analysis, of course!) to improve your understanding of the typical ideas in
the system 3. Bb5+ Nc6. For example, when do we take e5, or when do we push
d4-d5?} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nc6 4. O-O Nf6 $6 5. Re1 (5. e5 $1 $16 {
This move is even stronger. For example} dxe5 6. Nxe5 Qc7 (6... Bd7 {Here,
White wants to saddle his opponent with doubled pawns and simplify the
position. How should he continue?} 7. Bxc6 $1 (7. Nxc6 bxc6 $14) (7. Nxd7 Qxd7
$11) 7... bxc6 8. Nxd7 Qxd7 9. d3 $16 {White has achieved his goal and is
clearly better.}) 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Re1 $16) 5... e5 {This is the Spanish
approach.} (5... Bd7 6. c3 a6 7. Bf1 {leads to the main line.}) ({How should
we continue if Black plays} 5... a6 {?} 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. h3 {Preventing ...Bg4
in preparation for c3-d4. We are already familiar with this idea from our
Rossolimo camp.} e5 (7... g6 8. c3 Bg7 9. d4) 8. c3 Be7 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4
exd4 11. Qxd4 ({or} 11. Nxd4 Bd7 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Bf4 $14) 11... O-O 12. Nc3 Be6
13. Bf4 $14 {White has a stable advantage.}) 6. c3 Be7 ({After} 6... a6 {
we again take the knight} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 {and follow up with d4:} 8. d4 cxd4 9.
cxd4 exd4 10. e5 $1 {This direct continuation is very strong in this situation.
White can also achieve some advantage in a quieter way:} (10. Nxd4 Bd7 11. Nc3
Be7 12. Bf4 O-O 13. Qd3 $14 (13. Qf3 $14)) (10. Qxd4 Be7 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Bf4
$14) 10... dxe5 11. Nxe5 $16 {White has a strong initiative and Black will
have to make some concessions in order to complete his development.}) ({If} 
6... Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 {both, the slow and the fast approach work:} 8. g4 (8. d3 {
is also good. White's strategy is well-known from the Spanish.} Be7 9. Nbd2 O-O
10. Nf1 a6 11. Ba4 (11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Ng3 Bg6 13. Nh4) 11... b5 12. Bc2 Re8 13.
Ng3 (13. g4 $5 Bg6 14. Ng3) 13... Bg6 14. Nh4 Rc8 15. Ngf5 {intending g4,
creating an initiative on the kingside.}) 8... Bg6 9. d4 $1 $16 {with a strong
initiative for White. Black is lagging with his kingside development. We can
conclude that ...Bg4 is not justified in this position.}) (6... g6 7. h3 Bg7 8.
d4 Bd7 9. dxe5 $1 (9. d5 Ne7 10. Bf1 O-O 11. c4 Ne8 $132 {[%cal Yf7f5]}) 9...
dxe5 10. Qd6 $16) 7. d4 $1 Bd7 {This is an instructive moment: We may ask
ourselves: "Should we take on e5 or play d5...?" If Black's bishop is
developed to e7, we play d5, while if this bishop is on g7, we play dxe5. In
the latter case, Black would be ready to prepare counterplay with ....f5.} 8.
Bf1 {Not necessary.} (8. d5 $5 Nb8 9. Bf1 (9. Bd3 $5) 9... O-O (9... Bg4 {
is not justified. After} 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 {White has the pair of bishops
and a big space advantage. For example} h6 12. g3 O-O (12... Nfd7 13. h4 $16)
13. c4 (13. a4 Nbd7 14. c4) 13... Nbd7 14. Nc3 Nh7 15. h4 $16) 10. a4 ({
The combination} 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. d6 {is not impressive at this point though
White is also slightly better after} Nc6 12. dxe7 Qxe7 $14) (10. c4 $5 {
[%cal Yb1c3] also leads to a nice advantage for White.}) 10... Ne8 (10... Bg4
11. h3 Bh5 12. Nbd2 Nbd7 13. Bd3 a6 14. a5 Rb8 15. c4 Ne8 16. g4 Bg6 17. Nf1
$16 {[%cal Yf1g3]}) 11. Na3 f5 (11... g6 12. Bh6 Ng7 13. Nc4 f5 14. Nfd2 f4 15.
b4 $16) 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Nc4 $16 {Later, White can occupy e4 with a knight.})
(8. dxc5 dxc5) 8... O-O (8... Bg4 $6 {Black puts pressure on White centre but
White can simply play} 9. d5 {and gain a big advantage. For example} Nb8 10. h3
Bxf3 ({A sample line after} 10... Bh5 {runs} 11. a4 O-O 12. g4 (12. Nbd2 Nbd7
13. c4 Ne8 14. g4 $1) 12... Bg6 13. Nbd2 Nbd7 14. c4 $1 (14. Bd3 $2 {[%cal
Yd2f1]} Nxd5 $1) 14... a6 15. a5 Rb8 16. Bd3 b5 17. axb6 Rxb6 18. Nf1 Qb8 19.
Ng3 Qb7 20. Bc2 Rb8 21. g5 Ne8 22. h4 f6 23. h5 Bf7 24. Nf5 Bf8 25. g6 hxg6 26.
hxg6 Bxg6 27. N3h4 Bf7 28. Qg4 Kh8 29. Ra3 $1 $18 (29. Kg2)) 11. Qxf3 h6 {
Black's idea is to prepare ...Bg5 to exchange the dark-squared bishops. White
should try to keep the pair of bishops on the board. Despite the position
being closed for now, it may open up at a later point. How should White
prevent Black's plan?} (11... a6 12. a4 h6 13. g3) 12. g3 $3 ({Playable,
although too sophisticated is} 12. a4 Nfd7 13. g3 Bg5 14. Nd2 {with the idea
of playing h4 on the next move.} {If} h5 {then} 15. h4 Bh6 (15... Be7 16. Nc4)
16. Qxh5) 12... Nh7 13. h4 $3 {We not only prevented Black's plan but also
prepared Bh3, activating our light-squared bishop. The game might continue with
} Nd7 14. a4 O-O 15. Nd2 Qc7 16. Nc4 Rab8 (16... Rac8) 17. Bh3 Kh8 18. Bd2 $16)
9. h3 $6 (9. d5 $1) 9... Qc7 $6 ({Black misses his chances to get an
approximately equal game with} 9... cxd4 $1 10. cxd4 exd4 11. Nxd4 d5 $1 (11...
Re8 12. Nc3 $14) 12. e5 Ne4 $132) 10. a4 $6 {Both players keep missing their
chance until White grabs it on move eleven!} (10. d5 $1 $16 Na5 11. c4 (11. b4
$5 cxb4 12. cxb4 Nc4 13. a4 $16) 11... a6 12. Nc3 Rfb8 13. a4 b6 14. Bd2 Qc8
15. Bd3 Ne8 16. Kh2 Nc7 17. Ne2 Nb7 18. g4 Bf8 19. b3 (19. Ng3) 19... b5 20. a5
bxc4 21. bxc4) 10... Rfe8 $6 ({Again, Black could have exchanged on d4.} 10...
cxd4 $5 11. cxd4 exd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Bc6 14. Nc3 $132) 11. d5 $1 {
Finally, White makes this strong move and gets the advantage. Regardless of
where the knight retreats, Black gets an inferior version of the Spanish.} Na5
(11... Nb8 12. Nbd2 Na6 (12... Bc8 13. Bd3 Nbd7 14. c4 Nf8 15. Nf1 Ng6 16. Ng3
Bd7 17. Bd2 $16) 13. Nc4 Rac8 14. Bd2 (14. Nfxe5 $5 dxe5 15. d6 Bxd6 16. Qxd6
Bc6 17. Qxc7 Nxc7 18. f3 $16) 14... Bf8 15. b4 cxb4 (15... Qd8 16. b5 Nb8 17.
Nh2 $16) 16. cxb4 $18 {White has a decisive space advantage on the queenside
whereas a Black has no counterplay whatsoever.}) {Black has a positional
threat - what is it and how do we stop it?} 12. c4 $1 (12. Nbd2 c4 $1 $15 {
Fixing the structure on the queenside and vacating the c5-square, which the
a5-knight can occupy! For example} 13. Be2 a6 14. Nf1 b5 (14... Nb3) 15. axb5
axb5 16. Be3 Nb7 17. Ng3 Nc5) (12. Be3 c4 13. Nbd2 a6) (12. b3 c4 13. b4 Nb3
14. Ra2 Nxc1 15. Qxc1 a5 16. b5 Bd8) (12. Na3 $5 c4 $2 13. Nd2 $18 {[%csl Rc4]}
) 12... a6 13. Nc3 Reb8 14. Kh2 $5 {A high-level move, preparing g4 with an
attack on the kingside.} (14. Kh1) 14... Ne8 (14... b5 $2 15. cxb5 axb5 16.
Nxb5 Bxb5 17. Bxb5 $18 {is not enough for Black.}) 15. Bd3 Qc8 (15... g6 16.
Bd2) 16. Bd2 b6 (16... Kh8 17. Ne2 b6 18. g4 (18. Ng3)) 17. g4 Nc7 {I don't
like this move since ...b5 cannot be realised.} (17... h5 18. gxh5 Bxh3 19. Rg1
) 18. Ne2 $1 $18 {Now, Black cannot play ...b5 yet because this would drop the
a5-knight!} Qe8 (18... Nb7) 19. Ng3 Nb7 {Black is ready to play ...b5, but
White has good ways to deal with it.} 20. b3 $3 Bf8 21. Rg1 b5 22. a5 $1 {
[%csl Rb7,Rc7,Rd7,Rf8] This was the point behind b3 - completely restricting
Black's pieces!} Qd8 (22... Nd8 23. g5 bxc4 24. bxc4 Rb7 25. Bc3 Rab8 26. Bc2
Rb4 27. Qe2 (27. Bxb4 cxb4 28. Ne1 Nb7 29. Nd3 Nc5) 27... Bc8 28. Nf5) (22...
bxc4 23. bxc4 (23. Bxc4 $2 {gives up control of b5.} Nb5)) 23. Nf5 Ne8 (23...
Bxf5 24. gxf5 $18) 24. g5 b4 25. Nh6+ $1 {White opens the g-file with the help
of this sacrifice - his attack crashes through.} (25. Rg3 {was another good
option - improving the position before going for concrete play.}) 25... gxh6
26. gxh6+ Kh8 27. Ng5 Qf6 28. Qh5 Nd8 29. Rg3 $2 {Needlessly giving Black a
chance to fight back.} (29. Rg2 $18) 29... Bxh6 (29... Qxf2+ $1 30. Rg2 Nf6 $1
{White is still winning according to computer after} 31. Qd1 $1 {but it is
clear that this should have been avoided.}) 30. Rag1 Ng7 31. Qh4 {Black has no
good defence against the threat of 32.Nxf7+ Qxf7 33.Qxh6 +-.} Nde6 32. dxe6
Nxe6 33. Qxh6 Qg6 34. Nxe6 Qxh6 35. Bxh6 Bxe6 36. Bg7+ Kg8 37. Bf6+ 1-0

