{A very instructive game with the "Spanish set-up" in the system 3.Bb5+ Nc6!} 
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nc6 4. O-O Bd7 {Our basic idea is to play c3-d4.
However, in this particular situation, 5.Re1 is more accurate.} (4... a6 5.
Bxc6+ bxc6 6. h3 (6. e5 $16) 6... Nf6 7. Re1 e5 8. c3 Be7 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4
exd4 11. Nxd4 Bd7 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Bf4 $14) 5. Re1 e5 $6 (5... a6 6. Bxc6 Bxc6
7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nf6 (8... Bd7 9. c4 $14 (9. Nc3) (9. Bg5)) 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10.
Qf3 $1 e5 11. Nd2 Be7 12. Nc4 O-O 13. Bg5 $16 {[%cal Ya1d1]}) (5... Nf6 $1) 6.
c3 a6 7. Bf1 $16 ({I would have preferred} 7. Bxc6 $5 $16 Bxc6 8. d4 Qc7 {
Now, we see a plan that we definitely should know and must remember:} 9. dxe5
$1 dxe5 10. c4 $1 {We change the pawn structure to our advantage. White's
knight gets access to the outpost on d5 while Black's knight cannot get to d4!}
Nf6 11. Nc3 Be7 12. Nd5 $16 {Black cannot tolerate this knight and when he
takes it White gets a powerful protected passed pawn.} (12. Bg5 $5)) 7... Bg4 (
7... Nf6 8. h3 $5 {[%cal Yd2d4]} (8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 Bg4) 8... g6 (8... Be7 9.
d4 O-O 10. d5) (8... g5 9. Nxg5 Rg8 10. d4 h6 11. Nf3 Bxh3 12. d5 Ne7 13. a4
Bg4 14. a5 Ng6 15. Qa4+ Bd7 16. Qb3 Rb8 17. Qb6 Qxb6 18. axb6 Be7) 9. d4 Bg7
10. dxc5) 8. h3 Bh5 (8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Nf6 10. d4 {Obviously, this move is not
possible - we allow it for educative reasons!} (10. d3 $1 Be7 11. Be3 O-O 12.
Nd2 $14 {White's bishop on f1 will be activated at some point.}) 10... Be7 11.
d5 Nb8 12. a4 $1 (12. c4 $5) 12... h6 {We already know the next idea: White
fights against ...Bg5.} 13. g3 $3 (13. a5 $5 Nh7 14. g3 Bg5 15. Nd2 {[%cal
Yh3h4]}) 13... Nh7 (13... Nbd7 14. Nd2 (14. a5)) 14. h4 $1 $16) 9. g4 Bg6 10.
d4 Nf6 11. d5 {Closing the centre is very powerful - let's see how White is
going to deploy his pieces after this.} Na7 (11... Nb8 12. Nbd2 Nbd7 13. a4 Be7
(13... b6 14. c4 Be7 (14... h5 15. g5 Nh7 16. h4 $16) 15. Nh4 $1 (15. Bd3 $2
O-O (15... h5) (15... h5 $3 $36) 16. Nf1)) 14. a5 (14. Bd3 Nxd5) 14... O-O 15.
c4 $3 Ne8 16. Bd3 Nc7 17. Nf1 b5 18. b3 (18. axb6 Nxb6 19. Bd2 (19. Ng3 Rb8 20.
b3 Qd7 21. Kh2 $16) 19... Nd7 20. Ng3 Qb8 21. b3 Qb7 22. h4 h6 23. h5 (23. g5)
23... Bh7 24. g5 hxg5 25. Nxg5 Rab8 26. Bc2) 18... bxc4 19. bxc4 Rb8 20. Ng3
Rb4 21. Bd2 Qb8 22. h4) 12. Nbd2 Be7 13. a4 (13. Bd3 $4 Nxd5) ({According to
the computer} 13. Nh4 $3 {is even stronger!} h6 14. Nf5 Bxf5 15. exf5 $1 $16 (
15. gxf5 $5)) 13... O-O (13... h5 14. Nh4 (14. g5 Nh7 15. h4)) 14. a5 Nd7 (
14... Re8 15. c4 (15. Bd3 Nxd5)) 15. c4 $3 (15. Nc4) 15... Qc7 16. Bd3 $1 {
A strong regroupment - White prepares Nf1-Ng3.} Rfb8 17. Nf1 b5 {How do we
continue? We have two good ways:} 18. axb6 $1 (18. b3 $16 bxc4 19. bxc4 Rb4 20.
Ng3 Rab8 21. Bd2 (21. h4 h6 22. g5 h5 23. Nh2) 21... h6 22. Kh1 $1 {It is best
to ignore the rook on b4 and continue preparing our attack on the kingside.} (
22. Bxb4 $2 cxb4 23. Rb1 Nc5 $132 {Our attack is much weaker without our
dark-squared bishops, and Black's knight is beautifully placed on c5.}) 22...
Rb2 23. Rg1 $16 {[%cal Yg3f5] Black's rooks are active, but without support
from other pieces, they fail to create threats.}) 18... Rxb6 19. b3 $3 Nc8 20.
Ng3 (20. Bd2 $5 Rb7 21. Ba5 Qb8 22. Bc2 $16) 20... a5 21. h4 f6 22. g5 Nf8 (
22... fxg5 23. hxg5 $16) ({I want to point out the following instructive
variation, in the spirit of the King's Indian:} 22... Rb4 23. h5 Be8 24. g6 $1
h6 {Now sooner of later a crushing sacrifice on h6 will happen.} ({If Black
takes the pawn, White's knights enter the attack with gain of tempo. For
example} 24... hxg6 25. hxg6 Bxg6 26. Nh4 Bh7 27. Qg4 Kh8 28. Kh1 $18 (28. Ngf5
$18)) 25. Nf5 Bf8 26. Nh2 Kh8 27. Ng4 Nb8 28. Kh1 Ra7 29. Rg1 $18) 23. Kh2 Be8
24. Rg1 Kh8 25. Nf5 $18 {Black cannot withstand White's attack.} g6 26. Nxe7 (
26. h5 $1 gxf5 27. g6 hxg6 28. hxg6 Nxg6 29. exf5 Nf4 30. Bxf4 exf4 31. Qe2 Bf7
32. Rg4 $18 {[%cal Ya1g1] This is the computer solution.}) 26... Qxe7 27. gxf6
Qxf6 28. Bg5 Qf7 29. Be3 Rba6 30. Ng5 Qf6 31. Rg3 R6a7 32. Qd2 Ne7 33. Rf3 Qg7
34. Nf7+ Qxf7 (34... Bxf7 35. Bh6 Qg8 36. Qg5 Nd7 37. Qxe7 $18) 35. Rxf7 Bxf7
36. f4 Nd7 37. Qc3 Kg8 38. fxe5 dxe5 39. Bf2 g5 40. hxg5 Ng6 41. Bf1 a4 42. b4
cxb4 43. Qxb4 Rb8 44. Qxb8+ 1-0

