1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. O-O Bd7 5. Re1 Nf6 6. c3 a6 {White has some
alternatives:} 7. Bf1 (7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. d4 $5) (7. Ba4) 7... Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3 9.
Qxf3 g6 $6 {This looks logical yet I consider it a mistake!} (9... e6) 10. d3 {
White is going to slowly prepare d4.} ({After} 10. Qd1 {Black can play} Bh6 $5
{, exchanging one of White's bishops. We should strive to keep the bishop pair
instead.}) 10... Bg7 11. Be3 Nd7 12. Nd2 O-O 13. Qd1 b5 {Now, we have two very
good ways to play:} 14. Nf3 (14. a3 {with the idea to stop ...b4:} b4 (14... a5
15. Nf3 b4 16. d4 $16) 15. axb4 cxb4 16. d4 $16 {with a strong centre.}) 14...
b4 15. d4 bxc3 16. bxc3 e5 17. d5 $5 $16 {This leads to an excellent version
of the King's Indian for White. Still, I prefer 17.dc5!} (17. dxc5 $1 Nxc5 18.
Bxc5 dxc5 {Now, we can either play a better endgame or a middlegame with a
classical advantage:} 19. Bc4 $14 (19. Qa4 Qc7 20. Bc4 $14)) 17... Ne7 18. Qa4
h6 (18... f5 $2 19. Ng5 {[%cal Yg5e6]}) 19. Rab1 Qc7 20. Nd2 {A prophylactic
move directed against ...f5.} f5 21. f3 f4 22. Bf2 g5 23. Nc4 a5 24. Rb5 h5 25.
Reb1 Nf6 26. Rxa5 Rxa5 27. Qxa5 Qc8 28. Nxd6 Qd7 29. Qxc5 g4 30. hxg4 hxg4 31.
Rb7 Qd8 32. Qb6 Qa8 33. Rxe7 g3 34. Bc5 Qxa2 35. Nf5 Nh5 36. Qg6 Rxf5 37. Re8+
Rf8 38. Rxf8# 1-0

