{I consider the following game to be a piece of art!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.
Bb5 d6 4. O-O Bd7 5. Re1 Nf6 6. c3 a6 7. Ba4 $5 {This is not our repertoire
choice, but the play has some similarities, so ... let's check it!} (7. Bf1 $1)
7... b5 8. Bc2 Bg4 9. h3 Bxf3 (9... Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 11. d4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 $3 Nxd4
13. cxd4 e6 (13... Rc8 14. Bd3 e6 15. f4 $2 d5 16. f5 Bb4 $1 $132 17. e5 $3)
14. f4 h6 15. f5 $16 Bh7 16. Bb3 e5 17. Nc3 {[%csl Rh7]}) 10. Qxf3 g6 11. d3 $1
Bg7 12. Be3 Nd7 13. Nd2 O-O 14. Rac1 $5 Nb6 (14... b4 15. Ba4 $14) 15. Qe2 {
Preparing Nf3 followed by d4.} a5 16. Nf3 a4 $6 (16... e5 $5 17. Red1 Rc8 18.
d4 exd4 19. cxd4 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 cxd4 21. Bxd4 Bxd4 22. Rxd4 Qg5 23. Rcd1 $14)
17. d4 $3 cxd4 (17... c4 18. d5 Ne5 19. Nxe5 $1 Bxe5 20. a3 $1 $16) (17... Nc4
18. dxc5 dxc5 19. Bxc5 Nxb2 20. e5 $16) 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 19. Bxd4 Nc4 20. Bxg7
Kxg7 21. b3 $3 Na3 22. Bd3 axb3 23. axb3 $18 {Black is more or less lost! The
knight on a3 can never get out.} Qb6 24. Qb2 f6 (24... Rfc8 25. Ra1 b4 26.
cxb4+ f6 27. Rxa3 Qxb4 28. Raa1) 25. Ra1 $1 b4 26. c4 $1 {The knight on a3
cannot be taken but cannot move either. Later, White will open a front on the
kingside where he is playing with an extra piece.} Qc5 27. Rac1 Ra5 28. Bf1 Rb8
(28... e5 29. Red1 Qb6 30. h4) 29. Re3 Qe5 30. Qe2 (30. Qxe5 fxe5 31. Bd3 $14)
30... Rc5 31. Rd1 $1 (31. g3 $2 Nb5 $3 $15) 31... Rbc8 32. g3 $1 Rb8 33. Rd5
Qa1 34. Rd1 Qe5 35. Kh2 $5 Qh5 36. Qd2 Rc7 37. Rd3 Qa5 38. h4 Qb6 39. Rd5 Rc5
40. Rd4 Rb7 41. Bh3 $1 Re5 42. f4 Ra5 43. Be6 Rba7 44. Kh3 $1 (44. h5 $4 Nb5 (
44... Nxc4)) 44... Rc7 45. Rd3 Rca7 46. Qe2 Qc6 47. R3d2 Qb6 48. Rf1 Qc5 49.
Kh2 Ra8 50. Bd5 Rf8 51. f5 $1 Ra7 52. Qf3 Rh8 53. g4 Rf8 54. g5 Kh8 55. Qg3
gxf5 56. exf5 fxg5 57. Qxg5 $1 e6 58. fxe6 Rxf1 59. Qd8+ Kg7 60. Rg2+ 1-0

