{An interesting game played by me in the dubious 5...a6?! line. I chose the
positional approach with c2-c4 rather than going for a fast attack with moves
like Nc3-Bg5, etc.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. O-O Bd7 5. Re1 a6 $6 {
To my surprise, Black made this common mistake!} 6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. d4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Rc8 (8... Nf6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Qf3 e5 11. Nd2 $3 Be7 12. Nc4 O-O 13. Bg5
$16 {[%cal Ya1d1]}) 9. c4 {I decided to play in positional style.} Nf6 10. Nc3
g6 11. f3 $1 Bg7 12. Be3 O-O 13. Rc1 e6 {Black made this move after a long
think. However, the computer rejects this idea.} 14. b3 b6 {Black has a
passive position; he can never play ...d5.} (14... d5 15. cxd5 exd5 16. e5 $1
Ne8 (16... Nd7 17. e6 $18) 17. f4 $16) 15. Qd2 Ba8 16. Red1 Qc7 (16... d5 17.
cxd5 exd5 18. e5 Nd7 19. e6 $16 (19. f4 $16)) 17. Bh6 $2 {I thought this to be
logical - exchanging Black's good bishop on g7 and leaving him with a passive
one on a8. However, it gives away part of White's considerable advantage.} ({
Best was} 17. Nde2 $16 Rfd8 18. Na4 Rb8 19. Qb4 $1 {and White wins a pawn.})
17... Bxh6 $1 18. Qxh6 Rfd8 19. Kh1 Qc5 $1 $14 {Highlighting the drawback of
exchanging the dark-squared bishops: Black's queen has no access to the
central squares.} 20. Na4 Qa5 21. Nc3 Qe5 $1 22. Qd2 {Despite Black's queen
being active, White still has some advantage because Black has no pawn breaks.}
Rb8 (22... d5 23. exd5 exd5 24. Re1 Qd6 25. Qg5 dxc4 26. Nf5 $18) 23. a4 Rbc8
24. Re1 Kg7 25. Rcd1 h6 26. Ra1 Qg5 27. Qb2 Qe5 28. Rad1 h5 29. Qf2 h4 30. f4
Qh5 31. Rd3 d5 $2 {Finally, Black commits a serious mistake in time-trouble.}
32. cxd5 exd5 33. e5 Ne4 {Black has an active knight on e4, but this does not
fully compensate him for the weaknesses in his pawn structure and the passive
a8-bishop.} 34. Qb2 $1 $16 Kg8 35. e6 f6 36. Kg1 Re8 37. f5 gxf5 38. Rf1 f4 39.
Nce2 Rc7 40. Nxf4 Qe5 41. Qe2 Rg7 42. Qh5 Qxh5 43. Nxh5 Rg6 44. Rh3 Bb7 45.
Rxh4 Rc8 46. Rhf4 1-0

