{An excellent performance by the Greek GM!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4.
O-O Bd7 5. Re1 Nf6 (5... g6 6. c3 Bg7 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 a6 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 (9...
bxc6 10. h3 $1 Nf6 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Bf4 $14) 10. Nc3 Nf6 11. d5 Bd7 12. e5 $1 (
12. h3 O-O 13. Be3 $14) 12... dxe5 13. Nxe5 $16) 6. c3 a6 7. Bf1 Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3
9. Qxf3 g6 $6 10. d3 Bg7 11. Be3 O-O 12. Nd2 b5 (12... Nd7 13. Qd1 ({Black may
dream about something like} 13. Qg3 $2 b5 14. Rab1 b4 15. c4 Nd4 $132) 13... b5
14. Nf3 Nde5 15. Nh2 $14) (12... e5 13. Bg5 $1 b5 (13... Qe7 14. Nc4) (13... h6
14. Bh4) 14. Be2 $3 {Preparing both Be2-Bd1-Bb3 and Nf1!} Qe7 15. Bd1 h6 16.
Bh4 $16) 13. a3 $1 {White can play a3 or the immediate Qd1 - White is better
after both moves.} (13. Qd1 $1) 13... Nd7 14. Qd1 a5 (14... b4 $2 15. axb4 cxb4
16. d4 $16) 15. Nf3 b4 16. d4 (16. Qa4 $5 Qc7 17. d4 Nb6 18. Qd1 $16) 16...
bxc3 17. bxc3 Qc7 18. Rb1 Rab8 19. Qc2 e5 20. dxc5 $1 {A practical and good
decision, leading in a classical advantage!!} (20. d5 {is strong according to
the computer. White's position is objectively better, but Black always has
practical counterchances similar to the King's Indian.} Ne7 21. Nd2 f5 22. f3
Kh8 23. Nc4 Ng8) 20... Nxc5 21. Bxc5 $1 {We must keep the c-file closed!} (21.
Bc4 $2 Ne7) 21... dxc5 22. Bc4 Bh6 23. g3 $1 (23. Qa4 $1 Rxb1 24. Rxb1 $16 Rb8
$4 25. Rxb8+ $18) 23... Kg7 24. Kg2 $1 {White calmly improves his position -
he has a strategically winning position.} Ne7 25. Red1 Rfd8 26. Rxd8 Rxd8 27.
Qb3 Nc8 28. Qb8 Rd7 29. Nxe5 Re7 30. Nxf7 Qxb8 31. Rxb8 Rxe4 32. Bd5 1-0

