1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. O-O Bd7 5. Re1 Nf6 6. c3 a6 7. Bf1 Bg4 8. h3
Bxf3 9. Qxf3 e6 {This is Black's best way of playing.} 10. Na3 $1 {This is a
very interesting plan for White - but you need to know what you are doing!} (
10. d3) (10. Qg3 $5) 10... Rc8 (10... b5 {has no point. We can continue with}
11. Nc2 Be7 12. d4 cxd4 13. Nxd4 $16) 11. Nc2 d5 12. exd5 $1 Nxd5 13. Rd1 $3 {
White intends to play d4 without accepting an isolated pawn.} g6 14. d4 cxd4
15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. Rxd4 Bg7 17. Rd1 Qe7 18. Qe4 $3 {Centralising the queen and
stopping ...0-0.} Rc7 (18... O-O $4 19. Rxd5 $18) 19. Bc4 $1 {White wants to
expel the knight from d5. Afterwards, he will activate his dark-squared bishop.
Great technique by Abbasov!} Nf6 20. Qe2 O-O 21. Bf4 e5 (21... Rc6 22. Rd2 $1
Nh5 (22... Rd8 23. Rxd8+ Qxd8 24. Rd1 Qe7 25. Bb3 $14 Ne8 $6 26. Bd5 (26. Ba4
b5 27. Bc2) (26. Qd3) 26... Rc8 27. Bf3) 23. Be3 (23. Bh2 Bh6) 23... Rfc8 24.
Bb3 Nf6 25. Rad1) 22. Be3 {Playing ...e5 has weakened Black's control of the
centre.} Nh5 23. Bb3 Kh8 24. Qd2 Rfc8 25. Bb6 Rc6 26. Bd8 Qf8 27. Qd7 b5 28.
Bd5 Nf6 29. Qxf7 Nxd5 30. Qxf8+ Bxf8 31. Rxd5 b4 32. Ba5 e4 33. Rad1 bxc3 34.
Bxc3+ Kg8 35. Kf1 Be7 36. Ke2 h5 37. Ke3 Rc4 38. Bd4 Ra4 39. a3 Rc2 40. Rd2 Rc1
41. Kxe4 h4 42. Kf3 Kf7 43. Re2 Rc7 44. Re4 Rac4 45. Be5 Rxe4 46. Kxe4 Rc2 47.
Bd4 Bf6 48. Kd3 Rc1 49. Bxf6 Kxf6 50. Ke3 Rb1 51. b4 Re1+ 52. Kf3 Re6 53. Kg4
