{In this game, BLACK played in an exemplary fashion. Although we are studying
the line for White, it's beneficial for our understanding to examine it.} 1. e4
c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 (4... g6 5. c3) (4... e6 5. c3) 5. Bd3 {
White wants to play c3-Bc2 and eventually d4.} Ngf6 6. Re1 g6 7. c3 Bg7 8. Bc2
({Possibly White should have played} 8. a4 {, for example:} b6 9. Bc2 O-O 10.
d4 {In my view, White seems to be doing well.} e5 11. dxe5 $1 (11. dxc5 Nxc5 $1
$132) (11. Nbd2 {allows the double-capture, known from the Spanish:} exd4 $1
12. cxd4 cxd4 $1 13. Nxd4 Bb7 $132 {Black is well compensated for the weak
pawn on d6 by his good piece play.}) (11. d5 {In spite of the computer rating
this move quite highly, I do not like it.}) 11... dxe5 {Now, I see at least
two good moves for White:} 12. Bg5 (12. Na3 b5) ({Although I personally hate,
the computer likes} 12. c4 $3 {with the idea} Bb7 13. Nc3 $16 {[%cal Yc3d5]})
12... Bb7 (12... h6 13. Bh4) 13. Na3 $16 {[%cal Ya3c4,Yc4d6,Yc4e3,Ye3d5]
Depending on the situation, this knight can go to d6 or e3-d5.}) 8... O-O 9. d4
e5 10. d5 $2 {It was better to take dxe5 or to stop ...b7-b5 by first playing
10.a4!?} b5 {First, Black makes sure that he has a good position on the
queenside; later, f5 will come.} 11. a4 (11. Nbd2 Nb6 (11... c4 12. b3 $1))
11... Nb6 {A good move - Black does not want to play ...Bb7.} 12. b3 Bd7 13. a5
Nc8 {Now, White can no longer open the position on the queenside, while Black
is better placed for play on the kingside.} 14. c4 Ne7 15. Nbd2 b4 16. Nf1 Ne8
17. Ra2 f5 ({The computer suggest to play} 17... Kh8 $3 $15 {first, with an
instructive follow-up:} 18. Ng3 Ng8 19. h3 Bh6 20. Bxh6 Nxh6 21. Qd2 Ng8 22.
