1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. c3 Ngf6 5. Qe2 ({Generally, we avoid the slow
} 5. d3 {since Black gets a good game after} g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Re1
a6 9. Ba4 b5 10. Bc2 e5 11. Nf1 Bb7 12. Ng3 Re8 {Black's pieces are placed
perfectly and if White dares to play} 13. d4 $2 {we of course reply with the
double capture:} exd4 14. cxd4 cxd4 15. Nxd4 d5 $1 $17) (5. Bd3 $5 {[%cal
Yd3c2,Yd2d4]}) 5... a6 6. Ba4 Qc7 7. Bc2 g6 8. d4 e5 9. O-O (9. dxe5 dxe5 10.
a4 (10. c4 $5 {[%cal Yb1c3,Yc3d5]})) 9... Bg7 10. dxc5 (10. dxe5 {was the
right capture, leading to the game but having avoided the possibility of 10...
Nxc5!} Nxe5 (10... dxe5 11. a4 {transposes to the game.}) 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. c4
$1 O-O 13. Nc3 {We will some point play Nd5, but we are not in a hurry. The
threat is stronger than the execution!} Bd7 14. Bg5 (14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 (15.
cxd5 b5 $132) 15... f5 $132) 14... Bc6 15. Rad1 $16) 10... dxc5 (10... Nxc5 $1)
11. a4 b6 ({Black is in very bad shape after} 11... O-O $2 12. a5 $1 Re8 13.
Nbd2 Nf8 14. Nc4 $16) 12. Na3 O-O 13. Bg5 Bb7 14. Nc4 Rfe8 ({When playing 14.
Nc4, White must have taken into account} 14... b5 {How should we continue now?}
15. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ya3b5,Ya4b5,Ye2b5]} (15. Ncd2 $2 c4 {[%cal Yd7c5]}) 15... b4
16. Nc4 $14) 15. Rfd1 $14 {White is better - he can make use of the weak
squares on the d-file.} Re6 16. Rd2 b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. Rxa8+ Bxa8 19. Na3 $1
{Forcing a weakening of the light squares.} b4 20. Nc4 Bc6 21. Qd1 h6 22. Bh4
bxc3 23. bxc3 Nb6 24. Nxb6 Qxb6 25. Bxf6 Bxf6 26. Bb3 Re7 27. Rd6 Kg7 28. h3
Qc7 29. Bc2 Qb7 30. Qd3 Re8 31. Qc4 Be7 $2 32. Rd1 (32. Rxc6 $1 Qxc6 33. Ba4
Qc8 34. Bxe8 Qxe8 35. Nxe5 $16) 32... Bf8 33. Ba4 $14 Re6 34. Bxc6 Qxc6 35. Rd5
f6 36. Nh4 Rd6 37. Qd3 Kf7 38. c4 Qa6 39. Kh2 Be7 40. Qg3 f5 41. exf5 Bxh4 42.
fxg6+ Kg7 43. Qxh4 Rxd5 44. cxd5 c4 45. Qe7+ Kxg6 46. d6 c3 47. Qe6+ Kh7 48.
Qf7+ 1-0

