1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. c3 Ngf6 5. Qe2 e6 (5... a6 6. Ba4 b5 7. Bc2)
6. O-O Be7 ({Black should play} 6... a6 7. Ba4 b5 8. Bc2 Bb7 9. d4 Be7 10. Re1
Rc8 {with a playable position.} 11. Bd3 $1 (11. Nbd2 cxd4) 11... O-O 12. Nbd2
cxd4 (12... c4 $2 13. Bc2) 13. cxd4 $14 {[%cal Yd2f1,Yf1g3]}) 7. d4 {If Black
belatedly plays ...a6, our bishop can directly return to d3!} O-O 8. Bd3 $5 Re8
(8... e5 {With the bishop on e7, we answer ...e5 with} 9. d5) 9. Nbd2 e5 10.
Re1 $2 {A very bad decision - especially with a queen on e2 against a rook on
e8!} (10. d5 $1 $14) 10... Qc7 $6 ({Black should have taken the opportunity
and gone for the double-capture.} 10... cxd4 $1 11. cxd4 exd4 12. Nb3 Bf8 $1
$15 {[%csl Re2,Ge8][%cal Ye8e2]}) 11. d5 $1 $16 Nf8 ({If} 11... a6 {then both}
12. c4 ({and} 12. a4 {are good.} Nf8 $2 13. a5 $16)) 12. Nf1 (12. a4 $1 Ng6 13.
g3 Bh3 14. Nc4 $14) (12. c4 $5 Ng6 13. g3 Bd7 14. Nf1 a6 15. Ne3 Rab8 16. a4
$16 {One day we'll play f2-f4!}) 12... Ng6 (12... Bg4 13. c4 Ng6 14. h3 Bxf3
15. Qxf3 h6 {What to play now?} 16. g3 $1 {Fighting against the plan ...
Nh7-Bg5 by preparing h4.} (16. g4 Nh7) 16... Nd7 17. h4 a6 18. a4 Rab8 19. b3 {
Black is left without any plan while we prepare our attack on the kingside.
For example} Ngf8 20. Bd2 Qd8 21. Ne3 $16) 13. g3 a6 14. a4 $1 $16 (14. c4 $5
$16) (14. b3 $5 $16 b5 15. a4) *

