{A very good game by White demonstrating typical ideas in the Moscow variation!
} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O Ngf6 5. Re1 {Whenever we can protect
e4 in this way we choose Re1!} g6 $6 6. c3 $1 a6 7. Bf1 Bg7 8. d4 e5 (8... O-O
9. e5 (9. Bf4)) 9. dxe5 $1 {Whenever Black plays ...e5 in combination with ...
g6-Bg7, we take on e5!} dxe5 $6 (9... Nxe5 $14 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12.
a4 b6 13. Nd2 $16) 10. Nbd2 $6 {This in inaccurate.} (10. a4 $1 $16 b6 11. Na3
O-O 12. Nc4 Qc7 13. Bg5 $16 (13. Qd6 Qxd6 14. Nxd6 $18) 13... Bb7 14. Qd6) (10.
Bg5 $1 O-O 11. a4 $1 (11. Nbd2) 11... b6 12. Nbd2 h6 13. Bxf6 (13. Bh4 $1 $16)
13... Bxf6 14. Nc4 Bb7 15. Qc2 (15. Nd6 Bc6 16. Bc4) 15... Qc7 16. Ne3 $16 (16.
Rad1 $16)) (10. c4 $1 $16) 10... O-O $2 ({Black should have continued with} 
10... b5 $1 11. a4 (11. c4 b4) 11... Rb8 $1 12. axb5 axb5 $132 {White should
be careful not to get worse after ...c4, ...Nc5.}) 11. a4 $1 {Finally, White
prevents ...b5.} b6 (11... Qc7 12. a5 $16) 12. Nc4 Bb7 13. Nd6 Bc6 14. Bc4 h6
15. Nh4 $1 $16 {Very powerful! White is threatening Nxg6 and Black's king
cannot move away since f7 needs protection.} b5 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rxa8 Qxa8 18.
Bxb5 Bxb5 19. Nxb5 Qc6 20. c4 Nxe4 21. Qf3 f5 22. Nc3 Nb6 23. b3 Qf6 24. Nxe4
fxe4 25. Qxf6 Bxf6 26. Nxg6 Ra8 27. h4 h5 28. g4 hxg4 29. h5 Kh7 30. Be3 Ra3
31. Rb1 Nd7 32. Rd1 Ra7 33. Rxd7+ 1-0

