{This is a game which I lost after mistakenly taking ...cxd4. However, White
played a perfect game!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Bd3 {
[%csl Gd4][%cal Yc2c3,Yd3c2,Yd2d4]} Ngf6 6. c3 b5 7. Bc2 Bb7 8. Re1 e6 9. d4
cxd4 $2 {This natural-looking move is indeed a mistake. Black should delay ...
cxd4 in order to keep the option of playing ...c4 or ...b4!} ({Black should
play something like} 9... Be7 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Nf1 Rc8 (11... a5) (11... Qc7)
12. Ng3 Qc7 13. Bd3 b4 (13... cxd4 $2 14. cxd4 $16)) 10. cxd4 Be7 11. Nbd2 $1 {
In this position this is much better than Nc3!} O-O 12. Nf1 Rc8 13. Ng3 {
It is difficult for Black to find a constructive plan.} Re8 (13... e5 14. Nf5
$1 $16 (14. d5 $16)) (13... d5 14. e5 $16 Ne8 15. Qd3 g6 16. Bh6 Ng7 17. Qd2
Nb6 18. b3 {White has a strategically winning position.}) 14. h3 Bf8 15. Bd2
$16 Qc7 16. Rc1 Qb8 17. Ba5 $1 {Completely blocking Black's play.} g6 18. Qd2
Qa8 (18... e5 19. d5 $16 (19. Bb3 $5)) (18... d5 19. e5 $18 Ne4 20. Qf4 $1 {
Even stronger than winning a pawn.} (20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. Bxe4 Rxc1 22. Qxc1 Bxe4
23. Rxe4 Rc8 $16) 20... Nxg3 21. fxg3 Ba8 22. Rf1 (22. Bd3 Nb6 23. b3 $18)
22... Nb6 23. b3 $18) (18... Ba8 19. Rcd1 $5 {[%cal Yc2d3,Yc2b1]} Nb6 20. b3
$16) 19. a3 Rc4 (19... d5 20. e5 Ne4 21. Qf4) 20. Bd3 Rxc1 21. Qxc1 Rc8 22. Qd2
Qa7 23. h4 e5 24. Bc3 (24. d5 Nc5 (24... Nb6 25. b3 Nfd7 26. h5 Nc5 27. Bc2 $16
) 25. Bc2 $16) 24... Ng4 25. Bb1 Bg7 26. Ba2 exd4 27. Bxd4 Bxd4 28. Nxd4 Nde5
29. Rd1 Ba8 30. f3 Nf6 31. Qg5 Ne8 32. Ngf5 $18 Kf8 33. Nxd6 Nxf3+ 34. gxf3
Nxd6 35. Qf6 Qc5 36. b4 1-0

