{[%evp 0,41,16,16,46,53,82,44,66,46,48,56,57,54,54,54,77,70,62,1,-3,-8,6,-15,
-23,-36,-11,-27,-27,-23,-23,-17,-7,-11,2,-11,20,5,33,17,33,58,75,66]} 1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. d4 $5 {This is a very interesting line for
White—it's easy to learn since there is not much concrete theory. Black must
play very precisely to keep the balance while we are executing typical ideas!}
(4. O-O {is another possible move order. For example} a6 5. Bxd7+ Bxd7 6. d4)
4... cxd4 (4... Ngf6 {This can transpose to the main line:} 5. Nc3 cxd4 6. Qxd4
e5 7. Qd3 a6 $2 8. Bxd7+ Bxd7 9. Bg5) 5. Qxd4 a6 (5... e6 6. Nc3 Ngf6 (6... a6
7. Bxd7+ Bxd7 8. Be3 $14) 7. Bg5 $16) (5... Ngf6 6. Bg5) 6. Bxd7+ Bxd7 (6...
Qxd7 {is a playable alternative. White can hope for a small advantage with} 7.
Nc3 {, for example} e5 (7... Nf6 8. Bg5) 8. Qd3 h6 (8... Nf6 9. Bg5) 9. a4 Nf6
10. O-O Qc6 11. Nd2 Be6 12. Rd1 Rc8 13. Nf1 $14 Be7 (13... Bc4 14. Qf3 $14) 14.
Ne3 O-O 15. Bd2 $14 (15. a5 $14)) 7. Nc3 Rc8 {Black can either start with this
move or play 7...e5 and 8...h6 right away—it's the same!} (7... e5 8. Qd3 h6
9. Nd2 $1 {Now the knight can go to e3 via c4!} (9. O-O) 9... Rc8 10. Nc4 Be6
11. Ne3 Nf6 12. O-O Be7 13. a4 $1 O-O 14. Rd1 {,etc - we have transposed to
the main line.}) (7... Bg4 8. Be3 $1 (8. Qd3 Nf6 9. Bg5 e6 10. h3 Bh5 11. O-O-O
$1 $36) 8... Nf6 9. O-O-O $36) (7... Nf6 $6 8. Bg5 $1 e6 (8... e5 $2 9. Qd3 Be6
10. O-O (10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Nd5 $16) 10... Be7 11. Bxf6 $16) (8... Rc8 9. O-O (
9. O-O-O $1 $16) 9... e6 (9... Bg4 10. Bxf6 gxf6 (10... Bxf3 11. Bg5 $16) 11.
Nh4 $16 {[%csl Rg4]}) (9... h6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Nd5 Bg7 12. c3 O-O 13. Qe3 $14
) 10. Rfd1 $14 (10. Rad1 Be7 (10... e5 $2 11. Qa7 $18) 11. e5 dxe5 12. Nxe5))
9. O-O-O $3 $16 {Remember this idea!} Be7 10. e5 $1 dxe5 11. Nxe5 Bc6 12. Nxc6
bxc6 13. Bxf6 $3 Bxf6 14. Qc5 Qc7 15. Ne4 Be7 16. Nd6+ Kf8 17. Rd3 $16 (17. Rd4
$16)) (7... e6 $5 {This is playable alternative!} 8. Be3 $5 $14 (8. Bg5 $5 f6 (
8... Qc7 9. O-O-O $5 (9. O-O)) 9. Be3 Ne7 10. O-O $14 Nc6 11. Qd1 Be7 12. Na4
$3 Rb8 13. Nb6 $16) 8... Rc8 9. O-O-O (9. Qa7 $5 {Even this amazing move is
interesting!}) 9... Qc7 10. Rhe1 $14) 8. O-O e5 (8... e6 $5 9. Rd1 $1) 9. Qd3
h6 (9... Bc6 10. Bg5 $1 (10. a4 $1) 10... Qc7 (10... Nf6 $2 11. Nd2 Be7 12.
Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Nc4 Be7 14. Ne3 $16) (10... f6 11. Be3 $16) (10... Be7 11. Bxe7
Nxe7 12. Rad1 $16) 11. Nd2 $14) (9... Nf6 $6 10. Bg5 Be6 (10... Be7 11. Bxf6
gxf6 (11... Bxf6 12. Qxd6) 12. Rfd1 (12. Nd5 Bb5 13. Qd2 Bxf1 14. Rxf1 Qd7 15.
Nh4) 12... Be6 13. Nh4) 11. Rfd1 Be7 (11... h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Nd5 $1 $16 {
--> see MODEL GAME Spasov-Ivanovic}) 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Qxd6 $16 (13. Nd2 Be7
14. Nf1 O-O 15. Ne3 Re8 16. Ncd5 Bf8 17. c3 $16)) 10. a4 $5 {Now, it's only
about plans! The computer sometimes gives equality, but this assessment is
wrong! Black must wait by moving his pieces up and down; no human can do that!
White has a pleasant edge! With 10.Nd2 and 10.a4 White has two good moves,
both leading to similar positions. I personally prefer 10.a4 - then we no
longer need to think about ...b5.} (10. Nd2 $14 Be6 11. Rd1 (11. a4) 11... Nf6
(11... b5 $4 {is a serious mistake. Black creates targets on the queenside
with incomplete development.} 12. a4 b4 13. Nd5 Bxd5 14. exd5 $18 Nf6 15. Nc4
Be7 16. Bd2 a5 17. c3 bxc3 18. Bxc3) 12. Nf1 (12. a4) 12... Be7 (12... b5 13.
Ne3 $14) 13. a4 O-O 14. Ne3 {This is the position we aim for! Black cannot
play ...d6-d5 (if we are careful enough), and he does not have any active
plan! White will improve his position with moves like Bd2-Be1! , a well-timed
f2-f3, and quite possibly a4-a5! If we can play a5-Na4-Nb6, followed by b3-c4,
White will win - as is demonstrated in some of the MODEL GAMES! etc etc} Qd7 (
14... Ng4 15. Nxg4 (15. Ned5) 15... Bxg4 16. f3 Be6 17. Be3 Qd7 (17... Qc7 18.
a5) 18. a5 Rfd8 19. Na4 Qc6 20. Nb6 Rc7 21. Rac1 (21. c3) 21... Bf8 22. c4 Kh8
23. b3 (23. b4)) (14... Nh5 15. Ned5) 15. Bd2 $1 {White has two good moves: 15.
Bd2 (which I prefer) and 15.a5.} (15. a5 $1 {is also good and similar to 15.
Bd2. Here are some sample lines:} Rfd8 (15... Qc6 16. Bd2 $1 $14 (16. Ncd5 $1
$14 Bxd5 17. exd5 Qc7 18. c4 Nd7 19. b4) 16... Bc4 17. Nxc4 Qxc4 18. Be1 (18.
Qxc4) (18. Qf3) 18... Qxd3 19. Rxd3 (19. cxd3 Rfd8 20. d4) 19... Rfd8 20. Rad1
(20. Kf1 $5 $14 Rc4 21. f3)) 16. f3 (16. Bd2 $1 Qc6 (16... d5 $2 17. exd5 Nxd5
18. Nexd5 Bxd5 19. Bxh6 Be6 (19... Rxc3 20. bxc3 gxh6 21. c4 Bc6 22. Qg3+) 20.
Qg3) 17. Be1 Re8 18. f3 Qd7 (18... Nh5 19. g3 $1 $14 (19. Ncd5 $6 Bxd5)) 19.
Na4 (19. Bh4 Nxe4 20. Qxe4) (19. Kh1 Rb8 20. Ncd5 $6 Bxd5 21. Nxd5 Nxd5 22.
Qxd5 Rbc8 23. c3 Qc6 $132) 19... Qc7 20. b3 (20. Nb6 Rcd8 21. c4 Nh5 22. g3 (
22. Ned5) 22... Nf6 23. b3 Nd7 24. Nbd5) 20... Red8 21. Nb6 Rb8 22. c4 $16 Nh5
23. g3 (23. Ned5)) 16... Rc5 (16... Qc6 17. Ncd5 (17. Bd2 $4 d5 $1 $17) (17.
Kh1 Qc5 18. Qd2 Bf8 $2 19. Na4 $1 Qc6 20. Nb6 Rc7 21. c4 $16) 17... Bxd5 18.
exd5 Qc7 19. c4 $14) 17. Bd2 $1 $14 (17. b4 Rc6 (17... Rc7 18. Na4 $14) 18.
Ncd5 Bxd5 19. exd5 Rcc8 20. c4 $14) 17... Re8 (17... d5 $2 18. Ncxd5 Bxd5 19.
Bb4 $3 Rcc8 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. exd5 $16) (17... Rc6 18. Be1 $16 (18. Ncd5 Bxd5
19. exd5 Rcc8 20. c4 $14)) 18. Na4 Rc7 (18... Rcc8 19. Nb6) 19. Nb6 Qc6 20. Bb4
$1 (20. b4 $1 $16 {[%cal Yc2c4]}) (20. c4 Nd7 $14) 20... Rd8 21. c4) (15. Ncd5
$2 {is a mistake since White ends up with a pawn on d5.} Bxd5 16. Nxd5 (16.
exd5 Nh7 17. c3 f5 $17) 16... Nxd5 17. exd5 (17. Qxd5 Rxc2 $17) 17... f5 $17 {
Black is better due to his mobile kingside majority.}) 15... Rfd8 (15... Rfe8
16. Be1 Qc7 17. f3 (17. a5 $1 $14) 17... Qb6 $6 (17... Nh5 18. Kh1 (18. g3)
18... Nf4 19. Qd2 Red8 20. g3 Nh5 (20... Ng6 21. h4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rg5,Gh4]
[%cal Ye7g5]}) 21. Ned5 $16) 18. a5 $1 Qc5 (18... Qc6 19. Na4 $3 $16 {Once
White can stabilize like this, it's game over!} Nd7 20. b3 Nc5 21. Nxc5 dxc5 (
21... Qxc5 22. c4 Bg5 23. Bf2 Bxe3 24. Bxe3 Qc6 25. Qxd6 $16) 22. c4 {
Preventing a possible ...c4 and cementing the outpost on d5.} Red8 23. Nd5 $16)
(18... Qxb2 $4 19. Rdb1 $18) 19. Na4 Qc6 20. Nb6 Rb8 21. c4 $18 {This position
is strategically lost for Black.}) 16. Be1 $1 Qc6 17. f3 Bc4 (17... Qb6 $6 18.
a5 Qc7 19. Kh1 $1 Rd7 (19... Qd7 $2 20. Na4 Rc7 21. Nb6 Qc6 22. c4 $18) 20. Bh4
$1 (20. Na4 $2 d5 21. Nb6 dxe4 $17) (20. Ncd5 $5 Bxd5 21. exd5 $1 Rdd8 22. c4
Re8 23. b4 $14) 20... Rdd8 21. Rd2 $14) (17... Bf8 18. a5 $14 (18. Kh1 $5) (18.
Bh4 $5)) 18. Nxc4 (18. Qd2 $5 $14) 18... Qxc4 19. Qxc4 Rxc4 20. Kf1 $1 $14 Kf8
21. Ke2 Ke8 22. Rd3 Rd7 23. a5 {White has a small but stable advantage in this
endgame.}) 10... Nf6 11. Nd2 (11. Nd5 $2 {would be a positional mistake. We
must both our knight direct to d5!} Nxd5 12. exd5 Be7 13. c4 O-O 14. a5 f5 $17)
11... Be7 12. Rd1 O-O (12... Bg4 13. f3 Be6 14. Nf1 O-O (14... Bc4 15. Qd2 O-O
16. Ne3 Be6 17. Qd3 $14 (17. Kh1 $14)) 15. Ne3 $14) (12... Be6 13. Nf1 Bc4 {
This doesn't achieve anything.} 14. Qd2 {The queen steps away, followed by Ne3.
} O-O 15. Ne3 $16) 13. Nf1 Be6 14. Ne3 Qc7 {White has a deep positional plan:}
15. Bd2 $5 {White's aim is to activate this bishop by playing Be1-f3-Bh4! For
example} Rfd8 ({Black cannot target f4.} 15... Nh5 $2 16. Ncd5 $16) (15... Bc4
16. Nxc4 Qxc4 17. Qxc4 Rxc4 18. f3 Rfc8 19. Be1 $14) 16. Be1 $1 $14 (16. f3 $6
d5 $1 $132 17. exd5 Bc5) 16... Bc4 (16... Qc5 17. a5 $16 Bf8 18. Na4 Qc6 19.
Nb6 Rc7 20. f3 Be7 21. c4 Nd7 22. Nbd5 $18) 17. Qd2 (17. Nxc4 Qxc4 18. Qxc4
Rxc4 19. f3 Rdc8 20. Bh4 $14) 17... Bf8 (17... Qc5 18. a5 Be6 19. Na4 Qc6 20.
Nb6 (20. f3 $2 d5 $1 $19) 20... Nxe4 21. Nxc8 Rxc8 22. Qd3 $14) 18. a5 Be6 19.
f3 Rd7 20. Bh4 $1 $16 {White has executed his plan and is somewhat better.
After} (20. Na4 $2 d5 $3 $132) 20... g5 {White simply replies} 21. Bf2 {
, having created new weaknesses.} *

