1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 a6 6. Bxd7+ Bxd7 7. Nc3 e5 8.
Qd3 Nf6 $6 (8... h6) (8... Rc8) 9. Bg5 Be6 10. O-O ({After} 10. Bxf6 $5 gxf6
11. O-O Rc8 {White can go for the positional exchange sacrifice.} 12. Nh4 $1 (
12. Rfd1 $16) 12... Bc4 13. Qd2 Bxf1 14. Rxf1 Be7 15. Nd5 Qd7 16. Nf5 Bd8 17.
c3 Rg8 18. g3 $18) 10... Rc8 11. Rfd1 h6 12. Bxf6 $1 (12. Bh4 $2 g5 13. Bg3 Qc7
$132) 12... Qxf6 13. Nd2 $14 (13. Nd5 $1 {was very strong.} Qd8 14. c3 Bxd5 15.
Qxd5 Qc7 16. Ne1 {White is going to transfer his knight do d5 via c2-e3 or
c2-b4!} Be7 (16... Qc6 17. Qd3 $1 {We must keep the queens on the board to
achieve a tangible advantage.} ({After} 17. Nc2 Qxd5 18. Rxd5 Kd7 19. Ne3 g6
20. Rad1 Ke6 21. R5d3 Rc6 $14 {White is only slightly better.}) 17... Be7 18.
Nc2 O-O 19. Nb4 Qc4 20. Nd5 $16 Qxd3 $4 21. Nxe7+ $18 (21. Rxd3 $16)) 17. Nc2
O-O 18. Qd3 Rfd8 {Let me make two pointless moves with White to demonstrate an
important strategic idea:} 19. h3 Bg5 {Black has prevented Ne3.} 20. Rab1 a5 {
Preventing Nb4, but creating new weaknesses.} 21. Na3 $1 $16) 13... Qd8 (13...
b5 $2 14. a4 b4 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 Be7 17. Qxa6 Rxc2 18. Qb5+ Kf8 19. Ne4
Qg6 20. Qb8+ $18) 14. Nf1 {The knight is on its way to d5.} Bc4 (14... Be7 15.
Ne3 O-O 16. Ncd5 Bg5 17. c3 Bxe3 18. Nxe3 Rc6 19. Rd2 $14) 15. Qd2 Be7 16. Ne3
Bg5 (16... Be6 17. Nf5 Bxf5 18. exf5 O-O 19. Nd5 $16) 17. Qxd6 $1 Qxd6 18. Rxd6
Bxe3 19. fxe3 $16 O-O 20. Rad1 f5 (20... b5 21. a3 a5 22. R1d2 b4 23. axb4 axb4
24. Nd5 Bxd5 25. exd5 $18 (25. R6xd5)) 21. exf5 Rxf5 22. Rd8+ Rf8 23. Rxc8 Rxc8
24. a3 $5 Rc7 25. Kf2 Bf7 26. Rd6 Kh7 27. e4 $1 {White gets a great square on
e3 for his king.} Bc4 28. Ke3 Bf7 29. Rd2 Kg8 30. Nd5 Rc5 (30... Bxd5 31. exd5
$18) 31. c3 Be6 32. Nb4 Kf7 33. Nd3 Ra5 34. Rd1 Ke7 35. Rf1 Bc4 36. Rf5 Ke6 37.
Rf8 Bb3 38. Rb8 {Black's main mistake in this game was allowing Bg5-Bxf6.} 1-0

