{In this excellent game, White managed to play the a5-Na4-Nb6 plan, and
naturally, he got a completely winning position!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+
Nd7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 a6 6. Bxd7+ Bxd7 7. Nc3 e5 ({Very rarely} 7... Bg4 {
is played. White may prepare castling queenside with} 8. Be3 $5 ({or play the
quiet} 8. Qd3)) 8. Qd3 Rc8 9. O-O ({What is happening after} 9. Bg5 {which
appears to be very strong at first sight?} {However, after} Qc7 {Black gets a
good game. For example} 10. O-O Be6 11. Rfd1 h6 12. Bh4 (12. Be3 Nf6) 12... g5
$1 13. Bg3 Nf6 $132 {This is a good position for Black.}) 9... h6 10. Nd2 (10.
a4) 10... Qc7 {Black stops Nc4.} (10... b5) 11. Rd1 Bg4 $6 {A double-edged
move: on the one hand, White wants to play f3, but on the other, White's king
can be temporarily exposed.} 12. Re1 ({White avoids} 12. f3 {since it may
offer Black some tactical chances on the a7-g1 diagonal.}) 12... Nf6 13. Nf1
Be7 14. Qg3 $5 g6 15. a4 $1 Be6 16. Ne3 Qc6 17. Qf3 Kf8 18. a5 $1 Kg7 19. Bd2 {
A very tense situation - if White manages to stabilise the position, Black
will end up in big trouble.} Qd7 $6 {I don't like this.} 20. Red1 (20. Qe2 $2
Rxc3 21. Bxc3 Nxe4 $44) 20... h5 21. Qe2 $1 h4 (21... Rxc3 $2 22. Bxc3 Nxe4 23.
Bxe5+ $18) 22. f3 $1 g5 ({If} 22... Nh5 23. Ned5 Bxd5 24. Nxd5 {the move} Rxc2
{is not possible due to} 25. Bh6+ $18) 23. Na4 $3 Qc6 24. Nb6 Rcg8 (24... Rc7
25. c4 $16) 25. c4 $16 {White has managed to consolidate his space advantage
and has a big advantage.} Nh5 26. Nbd5 Nf4 27. Qf2 Bf8 28. b3 $1 f6 29. Ng4
Bxg4 30. fxg4 h3 31. g3 Nxd5 32. exd5 Qd7 33. Qf3 Be7 34. Be3 Rc8 35. Ra2 Bd8
36. Qe4 Rf8 37. Rf1 (37. Qf5 $1 $16) 37... b5 $1 38. axb6 Qb7 39. c5 dxc5 40.
Bxg5 $5 Qxb6 (40... fxg5 41. Rxf8 Kxf8 42. Rf2+ Kg7 (42... Kg8 43. Qg6+ Qg7 44.
Qe8+ Kh7 45. Rf7 $18) 43. Qxe5+ Kh7 44. Rf8 Qg7 45. Qf5+ Kh6 46. Qe6+ Kh7 47.
Rf7 $18) (40... c4 $3 41. bxc4 Bxb6+ 42. Be3 Bxe3+ 43. Qxe3 Rxc4 $11) 41. Raf2
Qd6 42. Rf5 Be7 43. Bh6+ $18 1-0

