1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 a6 6. Bxd7+ Bxd7 7. O-O Rc8
8. Nc3 e5 9. Qd3 h6 10. Nd2 Qc7 11. Rd1 (11. Nd5 {is not good enough.} Qxc2 $17
) 11... Nf6 12. Nf1 Be7 13. Ne3 Be6 14. Bd2 O-O (14... b5 $6 15. a4 $1 b4 16.
Ncd5 $16) 15. Rac1 (15. a4 $1 {was the right move - it was time to prevent ...
b5.}) 15... b5 $1 16. Ncd5 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Qxd5 Qc4 19. Be3 Qxd5 20.
Rxd5 Rc6 {This ending is pleasant for Black. He has to remember one thing:
centralise the king!} 21. c3 h5 $3 {How did Black arrive at this decision?
Black wants to play ...g6-f5 (now he is ready to take with the pawn on f5),
intending ...Kf7-e6!} (21... f5 22. exf5 Rxf5 23. f4 (23. a4)) (21... f6 $6 22.
g4) ({With a pawn on h7, Black could have played the immediate} 21... g6 $2 {
which here drops a pawn.} 22. Bxh6 $18) 22. Kf1 g6 23. Ke2 f5 24. f3 Kf7 25.
Kd3 Ke6 26. Ra1 Rb8 27. b4 Rbc8 28. Bd2 Rc4 29. a4 {Now, something magical
happened:} Rxe4 $3 30. Rxd6+ (30. fxe4 fxe4+ 31. Kxe4 Rc4+ 32. Kd3 Kxd5 $17)
30... Bxd6 31. fxe4 Rc4 $15 {Black has the better endgame and he managed to
win. Super high-level play by Wesley So!} 32. axb5 axb5 33. exf5+ gxf5 34. Ra6
Rc8 35. Be3 Kd5 36. g3 e4+ 37. Kd2 Be5 38. Bc5 Kc4 39. Rh6 Rd8+ 40. Ke2 Bxc3
41. Rxh5 Rd2+ 42. Ke3 Rd5 43. Ke2 Rd2+ 44. Ke3 Rd3+ 45. Ke2 Rf3 46. Rg5 Bxb4
47. Bxb4 Kxb4 48. g4 Kc5 49. gxf5 b4 50. f6+ Kc4 51. Re5 Rxf6 52. Rxe4+ Kc3 53.
Re8 Rh6 54. Rc8+ Kb2 55. Kd3 Rh3+ 56. Kd4 Rxh2 57. Rb8 b3 58. Kc4 Kc2 0-1

