{In this fantastic game, we see the typical strategies when Black gets doubled
f-pawns after Bxf6.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. d4 Ngf6 5. O-O cxd4 6.
Qxd4 a6 7. Bxd7+ Bxd7 8. Bg5 $1 h6 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. c4 e6 11. Nc3 {White will
prevent ...b5 with a4 when Black is doomed to passivity.} Rc8 12. Kh1 h5 13. a4
h4 14. h3 $1 {White should not allow ...h3.} Be7 15. b4 a5 16. b5 $1 {A
counter-intuitive move - weakening c5, however Black's problem is that he has
no more knights to exploit this!} Qc7 17. Nd2 Qc5 18. Qd3 Rg8 19. Rae1 Qg5 20.
Rg1 {White has defended against Black only threat.} Qf4 21. Ref1 b6 22. Ne2 Qh6
23. c5 $5 {An amazing pawn sacrifice!} Rxc5 24. Nc4 Kf8 25. Nxb6 Be8 26. f4 f5
{Black is left to play tricks since the position is strategically won for
White.} 27. exf5 Rxf5 28. Rc1 Kg7 29. g4 Rc5 30. Rxc5 dxc5 31. Nc8 Bf8 32. Qd8
Qg6 33. f5 Qh6 34. g5 Qh5 35. Rg4 exf5 36. Nf4 Qh8 37. Qf6+ Kh7 38. Rxh4+ 1-0

