{[%evp 0,29,16,16,52,52,67,43,64,14,0,-17,-11,-9,-9,1,-33,-50,13,-20,-29,-19,
-20,-11,-14,-37,27,32,26,45,51,38]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. c3 $1 {
That is a very nice move order, trying to build a centre with c3-d4 as fast as
possible while avoiding the tons of theory after 4.0-0 a6 5.Bd3.} (4. O-O a6 5.
Bd3) 4... Ngf6 (4... a6 {This and other move orders, will just transpose to
the same position!} 5. Ba4 (5. Bd3 {can lead to the same position, but let's
stick with 5.Ba4.}) 5... Ngf6 (5... b5 6. Bc2 Bb7 (6... c4 {seems to be
premature. We can set problems with} 7. a4 Bb7 8. O-O Ngf6 9. axb5 axb5 10.
Rxa8 Bxa8 11. Re1 e6 12. Na3 $1 Qb8 13. d3 $1 cxd3 14. Bxd3 $16 {Black hasn't
developed his kingside while creating targets on the queenside.}) 7. d4 $14
cxd4 $2 {A the typical mistake - Black should keep the tension to have the
option ...b5-b4.} 8. cxd4 $16 e6 9. O-O Ngf6 10. Re1 Be7 11. Nbd2 O-O 12. Nf1
Rc8 13. Ng3 Nb6 14. h3 Re8 15. Bd3 $16) 6. Bc2 b5 (6... e5 7. d4 (7. a4 $1 {
REMEMBER THIS a4 MOVE - IN VARIOUS CASES! It seems to work very well for White.
..stopping ...b7-b5 and only then play d4!} b6 8. d4 Bb7 9. d5 $16 (9. O-O $14)
)) 7. d4 Bb7 8. Nbd2 e6 9. O-O Rc8 10. Re1 Qc7 11. Bd3 $14 {We will continue
with Nf1; for example} Be7 12. Nf1 cxd4 13. cxd4 O-O 14. Ng3 Rfe8 15. h3 Bf8
16. Bd2 Nb6 17. Ba5 $16 (17. b3 Qb8 18. Qe2 $16)) (4... g6 $2 5. d4 $1 (5. O-O
$5 Bg7 6. d4 cxd4 7. cxd4 a6 8. Ba4 b5 9. Bb3 $16) 5... cxd4 6. cxd4 Ngf6 7.
Nc3 a6 8. Be2 $1 $16 (8. Bd3 $16)) (4... e6 $6 {This is a careless move order
because now we have the time to play d4! first, and then after ...a6, return
with the bishop to d3 - which is its ideal position!} 5. d4 $1 Ngf6 6. Bd3 $14
Be7 7. O-O) 5. Bd3 $1 {Our plan: play a fast Bd3-Bc2 and d4! and only after
that will we castle!} g6 $1 (5... Ne5 $6 {An interesting idea, which however
does not work well in this position.} 6. Be2 $5 Nxf3+ (6... Ng6 7. Qc2 $1 {
Protecting the e4-pawn with the idea of playing d4 next.} Nf4 (7... Bg4 8. d4
cxd4 9. cxd4 Rc8 10. Nc3 $16) 8. Bf1 $1 {This may seem very odd - White has
made several moves with his bishop. However, he will win some tempi after d4 
(attacking the knight on f4), etc.} e5 9. d4 $16) (6... Nc6 $6 7. d4 $3 cxd4 8.
cxd4 Nxe4 9. d5 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 $1 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Ne5 12. O-O $16 Bd7 13. Nxe5 dxe5
14. Be3 g6 15. Qb3) (6... Nxe4 $4 7. Qa4+ $18) 7. Bxf3 e5 (7... g6 8. d4 $16)
8. d4 Be7 9. O-O (9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Qxd8+ Bxd8 11. Nd2 Be6 12. Be2 $14) 9... O-O
10. Be3 $14) (5... e5 6. O-O Be7 7. Bc2 O-O 8. d4 b5 9. Re1 Bb7 10. d5 $14 c4
$140 11. b3 $1) (5... e6 $1 6. Bc2 $1 Be7 (6... b5 $5 7. d4 $1 Bb7 8. Nbd2 $1 {
Be careful! We don't want to play an early Qe2! If possible, the queen should
stay on d1 for now.} Qc7 (8... cxd4 $2 9. cxd4 Rc8 10. O-O Be7 11. Re1 Qb6 12.
Nf1 O-O ({Black must avoid} 12... d5 $2 13. e5 Ne4 14. Ng3 {White is
threatening to take on e4 and after} Nxg3 15. hxg3 $16 {Black is left with
only passive pieces and might already be losing in a strategical sense.}) 13.
Ng3 $14) 9. O-O Be7 10. Re1 O-O 11. Nf1 Rac8 12. Bd3 a6 13. Ng3 Rfe8 14. h3 Bf8
15. Bd2 $14 (15. Be3 $14)) (6... c4 $2 7. Qe2 {After a premature ...c4, we
attack this pawn as fast as possible.} ({or} 7. b3) 7... b5 8. a4 Qa5 9. Na3 a6
10. O-O Bb7 11. axb5 axb5 12. d3 $16 (12. d4 $16)) 7. d4 Qc7 (7... O-O 8. O-O
$1 $14 (8. a4 $1 {This is another interesting approach - not necessary at all,
but very clever! Before castling, we stop ... b5 and prepare a possible Na3.}
b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Re1 a6 11. h3 Qc7 12. Na3 Rac8 (12... Bc6 $2 {intending ...
Qb7, is not working due to} 13. d5 $1 exd5 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. c4 $18) 13. Bd3
$14) 8... a6 9. a4 $5 {The same idea as on move 8!} (9. Re1) (9. Nbd2) (9. e5)
9... b6 10. Re1 Bb7 11. Na3 $14 (11. h3 Qc7 12. Na3 Rfe8 13. Bf4 $14)) 8. O-O (
8. a4 $1) 8... O-O 9. Re1 $1 (9. a4 $1 {This is connected with a very
interesting plan for White: playing a4 followed by Na3!} b6 10. Re1 Bb7 11. Na3
a6 12. Bd3 Rfe8 13. Bg5 $14 h6 14. Bh4 ({or} 14. Bd2)) 9... Rd8 $2 10. Qe2 e5
11. d5 Nf8 12. c4 Ng6 13. Nc3 $16) (5... d5 $6 6. e5 Ng4 {Now, White has two
promising options:} 7. Bb5 (7. e6 $1 {White will get lots of compensation
after this pawn sacrifice:} fxe6 8. Ng5 Nge5 9. Bc2 c4 10. O-O g6 11. d4 cxd3
12. Bxd3 $14) 7... a6 (7... e6 8. h3 Nh6 9. d4 $16) 8. Bxd7+ Bxd7 9. d4 $14 {
We have conceded the pair of bishops, but Black's knight will end up on h6.}) (
5... b5 $2 {has been played a few times, but simply does not work.} 6. Bxb5 $16
Nxe4 $4 7. Bc6 $18) (5... b6 {A playable move, though a bit passive.} 6. O-O {
Here it's a good idea to castle to have Re1 in reply to ... Bb7.} Bb7 7. Re1 e6
(7... g6 8. Bc2 Bg7 (8... c4 {is premature since we can immediately target
this pawn.} 9. b3 b5 10. Na3 Ba6 11. d3 cxd3 12. Bxd3 $16) 9. d4 e5 (9... O-O
10. Nbd2 $14 (10. e5) (10. Bg5)) 10. dxe5 (10. d5 $1 $16 {We generally do not
play d5 with a black bishop on g7, but here Black's b7-bishop is badly
misplaced after this.}) 10... dxe5 11. c4 $1 $16 {[%cal Yb1c3,Yc3d5] I don't
like this move in general, though here it is strong. White is fast in
occupying the square d5 with his knight.} (11. a4 O-O 12. Na3 a6 13. Nc4 $14) (
11. Bg5 $14) (11. Qd6 Qe7 (11... Bf8 $6 12. Qd3) 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 $14)) 8. Bc2
Be7 9. d4 O-O 10. Nbd2 a6 11. Nf1 b5 12. Ng3 $14 Rc8 13. h3 Qc7 14. Bd3 Rfe8
15. Bd2 Bf8 16. Qe2 {Black does not have active plans. If} g6 {then} 17. h4 $14
{is interesting.}) (5... g5 $6 {This is comparatively common in the Moscow,
but not in this position.} 6. h3 Rg8 7. Bc2 Ne5 8. d4 Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3 g4 10. hxg4
Bxg4 11. Qd3 $16 {It seems to me that Black's king is weaker in the long run.}
(11. Ba4+ $16)) (5... c4 $6 6. Bxc4 Nxe4 7. d4 $14) 6. Bc2 Bg7 (6... b5 7. d4
cxd4 (7... Bb7 $2 8. e5 $3 {This is even better than 8.Nbd2!} dxe5 9. dxe5 Bxf3
10. Qxf3 Nxe5 11. Qe2 Nc4 12. a4 $16) (7... Bg7 $2 8. e5 dxe5 9. dxe5 Ng4 10.
e6 $16 Nde5 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. exf7 $16 (13. f4 Nc4 14. exf7 Be6
15. Nd2 $16 Bxf7 16. Nxc4 Bxc4 17. Be3)) 8. cxd4 Bb7 9. Nbd2 Bg7 10. O-O O-O
11. Re1 Rc8 12. Bd3 $14 a6 13. Nb3 (13. a4)) (6... Bh6 $6 {This is a dubious
idea.} 7. d4 $1 Bxc1 8. Qxc1 $14 {For example} e5 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Na3 {
Preparing to target Black's weaknesses on the d-file.} Qe7 11. Qd2 O-O 12. h4
$16) 7. d4 O-O (7... e5 $6 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. a4 ({Even} 9. Qd6 $5 {is possible.}
Bf8 (9... Qe7 10. Qxe7+ Kxe7 11. a4 b6 12. Na3 Bb7 13. Nd2 Rhd8 14. f3 $16) 10.
Qd3 $16) 9... O-O 10. Na3 $16) (7... cxd4 8. cxd4 b5 $5 (8... O-O 9. Nc3 $14)
9. O-O Bb7 10. Re1 O-O 11. a4 $5 $14 (11. a3 $5 a5)) 8. O-O {Sooner or later
White is threatening to play e4-e5.} e5 (8... b6 $5 9. Re1 (9. e5 $6 Ne8) (9.
a4 $1 $14 Bb7 10. Re1 $14 e6 (10... e5 11. d5 $5 $14 (11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5
dxe5 13. Qxd8 (13. Qe2 $14) 13... Raxd8 14. f3 Rd7 15. Na3 Rfd8 16. Be3 $16)
11... a6 12. c4 $16)) 9... Bb7 10. Bg5 (10. e5 $6 dxe5 11. dxe5 Ng4 $132) (10.
a4 a6 11. d5 $14 (11. Bg5 $14)) (10. Nbd2 Qc7 11. a4 (11. Nf1 $6 cxd4 $1 12.
cxd4 Rfc8 13. Bd3 e5 14. dxe5 dxe5 $15)) 10... h6 11. Bh4 g5 (11... cxd4 12.
cxd4 g5 13. Bg3 Nh5 14. Nc3 Rc8 15. Qd3 $14) 12. Bg3 Nh5 (12... cxd4 13. Nxd4
$16) 13. Na3 $5 (13. e5 $5 Nxg3 14. hxg3 g4 $2 15. Qd3 $1 $16) 13... cxd4 14.
cxd4 Rc8 15. Qe2 Qc7 16. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Ya3c4]}) 9. dxe5 $1 {We already know
the principle: if Black plays ...e5 with a bishop on g7, we take on e5!} (9. d5
$2 b5 10. a4 b4 $132) 9... Nxe5 $1 (9... dxe5 10. a4 $1 b6 11. Qe2 (11. Na3 $16
Ba6 12. Bd3) 11... Bb7 12. Na3 $16) 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Qe2 $14 Be6 (11... Nh5
12. g3 $1 Bh3 (12... b6 13. c4 $1 $16 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yb1c3,Yc3d5]}) 13. Rd1
Qe8 14. Be3 b6 15. Nd2 $16) 12. Rd1 $1 {preparing to follow up with c4-Nc3-d5.}
(12. Bb3 $1 $14 {is also good.} Bxb3 13. axb3 Qb6 14. Qc2 Rad8 15. Bg5 {
1-0 Riff,J-Tahay,A/Escaldes AND 2017.} h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. c4 $14) 12... Qe7
13. c4 Rad8 14. Rxd8 Rxd8 15. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yc3d5]} *

