1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. c3 a6 5. Ba4 {In this case, I prefer Ba4
over Bd3. The bishop will end up on c2 in most cases, so there is no
difference. But in some lines, Bb3 may be a useful extra option.} b5 (5... g6
6. d4 cxd4 7. cxd4 b5 8. Bb3 $5) (5... Ngf6 6. Bc2) 6. Bc2 Bb7 7. d4 e6 8. O-O
Be7 9. Re1 Qc7 10. Nbd2 Ngf6 11. Nf1 O-O 12. Ng3 Rad8 ({A possible
continuation after the more natural 12...Rac8:} 12... Rac8 13. Bd3 Qb8 14. h3
cxd4 15. cxd4 Rfe8 16. Bd2 Bf8 17. Ba5 Ba8 18. Qd2 Nb6 19. b3 g6 20. h4 $14)
13. Qe2 Rfe8 14. a4 c4 15. Bd2 Bf8 16. h3 g6 17. Be3 h5 $2 {Black needlessly
weakens his position.} 18. Bg5 e5 19. Qd2 Kh7 {How should White continue?} 20.
b4 $1 $16 {A high-level move! White gets space on the queenside and uses the
fact that ...cxb3 is bad for Black:} Bg7 (20... cxb3 21. Bxb3 Kg8 22. Bxf6 Nxf6
23. Qg5 $18) 21. d5 $1 {White has an excellent version of the Closed Spanish.}
Ra8 22. Be3 Rf8 23. Rf1 Qd8 24. Ra3 Ng8 25. Ng5+ Kh8 26. Rfa1 Qe7 27. Qc1 Ndf6
28. R1a2 Nh7 29. Nxh7 Kxh7 30. Qa1 h4 31. Nf1 f5 32. f3 f4 33. Bf2 Rab8 34.
axb5 axb5 35. Ra7 $18 Qg5 36. Qe1 Bf6 37. R2a6 Rfd8 38. Rb6 Rd7 39. Rxb5 Ne7
40. Ra1 Qh6 41. Bd1 g5 42. Nd2 Rc7 43. Be2 Rbc8 44. Ra7 Ba8 45. Rxc7 Rxc7 46.
Nxc4 Bg7 47. Rb8 Bb7 48. Bb6 Rd7 49. Na5 Bxd5 50. exd5 e4 51. Bb5 Nxd5 52. Bxd7
Qf6 53. Qxe4+ Kh6 54. Qxd5 Qxc3 55. Qxd6+ Bf6 56. Rh8+ Kg6 57. Be8+ Kf5 58.
Qd5+ Be5 59. Rf8# 1-0

