1. Nf3 c5 2. e4 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. c3 Ngf6 5. Bd3 a6 6. Bc2 b5 7. d4 Bb7 8. Nbd2
e5 9. O-O $1 (9. d5 $1 {In this concrete position, IT IS EVEN BETTER TO DELAY
CASTLING AND ATTACK WITH OUR KING IN THE CENTER!} Be7 10. c4 O-O 11. a4 $3 {
Trying to clarify the situation on the queenside. If Black closes the
queenside with} (11. h3 g6 12. g4 Nb6 13. b3 $16) 11... b4 {then White could
have started an attack on the kingside and leave his king in the centre!} 12.
g3 g6 13. b3 Bc8 14. Qe2 (14. Nf1) 14... Nh5 15. Nf1 Ng7 16. g4 $16) 9... Be7
10. d5 O-O 11. Re1 {White's best continuations are c4 and b3.} (11. b3 $3 $14)
(11. c4 $1 $14 Nb6 12. b3 g6 13. Re1 Nh5 14. Bd3 b4 15. Nf1 Ng7 16. Bh6 f5 17.
exf5 gxf5 18. Ng3 e4 19. Nxe4 fxe4 20. Bxe4 $16) 11... g6 12. Nf1 (12. b3)
12... Nh5 13. g4 $2 {This is too much in my opinion. White should have played}
(13. Bh6 Ng7 14. h3 $16 {with a superior position due to Black's misplaced
bishop on b7. Black is not yet ready for} f5 $2 15. exf5 gxf5 16. Ng3 {After}
e4 {White gets a dangerous attack with the piece sacrifice} 17. Nxe4 $3 fxe4
18. Rxe4 Nf6 (18... Rf7 19. Rg4 $16) 19. Rh4 $18) 13... Ng7 $2 {After this
passive move, White is better again.} (13... Nf4 $1 $132) 14. Ng3 (14. Bh6 $14)
14... Nf6 15. h3 h5 16. Nh2 h4 17. Nh1 Nh7 18. f4 exf4 19. Bxf4 Bg5 20. Qd2 Qf6
21. Rf1 Rae8 22. Rad1 Bxf4 23. Rxf4 Qe7 24. Nf2 Bc8 25. Rf1 Ng5 26. Nf3 Nh7 27.
Nh2 Ng5 28. Nf3 Nh7 29. Ne1 Ng5 30. Ng2 Qd8 31. Kh2 Re5 32. Nxh4 Nxh3 33. Nxh3
Qxh4 34. Qf2 Qe7 35. Qg3 Nh5 36. gxh5 Rxh5 37. Rf5 Rh6 38. R1f3 Kg7 39. Kg2 f6
40. Nf2 Bxf5 41. exf5 Qe1 42. Re3 Qd2 43. Re7+ Rf7 44. Rxf7+ Kxf7 45. fxg6+ Kg7
46. Be4 Rh5 47. Qxd6 f5 48. Bf3 Rg5+ 49. Kf1 Qe3 50. Qd7+ Kxg6 51. Qe6+ Qxe6
52. dxe6 Kf6 53. Nd3 f4 54. Nxf4 Rf5 55. Nh5+ Ke7 56. Kf2 Rf8 57. Ke3 Kxe6 58.
b4 cxb4 59. Nf4+ Kd6 60. cxb4 Rc8 61. Bd1 Rc4 62. Nd3 Kc7 63. Bb3 Rh4 64. Nf4
Kb7 65. Ke4 a5 66. bxa5 Ka6 67. Ke5 Kxa5 68. Nd5 Rh1 69. Ke6 Rc1 70. Kd6 Rc8
