1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Nxd7 5. O-O Ngf6 ({Even high-level
players and even Grandmasters throw in the move} 5... g6 {, but it is almost
always a mistake! Exception: White chooses a setup with c2-c4.} 6. c3 $1 Ngf6
7. Re1 (7. Qe2 {is equally good.}) 7... Bg7 8. d4 cxd4 ({The absence of
light-squared bishops is in White's favour after} 8... e5 9. dxe5 dxe5 {
How should White continue?} 10. c4 $1 {An easy way to get the advantage! White
is going to put a knight on d5. For example} (10. Bg5 $5) 10... O-O 11. Nc3 Nb6
12. Qe2) 9. cxd4 O-O 10. Nc3 Nb6 (10... e5 11. dxe5 (11. Bg5) (11. d5 {is not
best (though White is also better here), because it does not make use of the
weak d5-square.}) 11... Nxe5 (11... dxe5 12. Bg5) 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Bg5 Qxd1
14. Rexd1 {White is better due to the weakness of d5 and Black's passive
dark-squared bishop.}) 11. Bg5 {White had different options. In any case he is
somewhat better due to his space advantage.} Qd7 $6 (11... h6 12. Bh4 $14) 12.
h3 $16 (12. Qb3 $16 {Here, the queen stands quite well on b3—the
light-squared bishops have been exchanged, so it cannot be easily harassed.})
12... Rac8 13. Qd3 Rfe8 14. a4 Nc4 15. b3 Na5 16. Nb5 (16. Rab1 Nc6 17. b4 $16)
16... Nc6 17. Rac1 d5 18. e5 Ne4 19. Bf4 Nb4 20. Qe2 a6 21. Nc7 Red8 22. Nxd5
Rxc1 23. Bxc1 Qxd5 24. Qxe4 e6 25. Qh4 Nd3 26. Rf1 Rc8 27. Bh6 Qd8 28. Bg5 Qe8
29. Rd1 Nb4 30. Bf6 Nd5 31. Bxg7 Kxg7 32. Ng5 h6 33. Ne4 Rc2 34. Rd3 Rc1+ 35.
Kh2 Qe7 36. Qg3 Qa3 37. Nd6 Qa1 38. Qf3 Rh1+ 39. Kg3 Qc1 40. Qxf7+ Kh8 41. Qe8+
Kg7 42. Qd7+ Kg8 43. Qxe6+ Kh7 44. Qd7+ Kg8 45. Qd8+ Kh7 46. Qd7+ Kg8 47. Qc8+
{1-0 Turkova,K-Skrabakova,K/Prievidza 2014.}) 6. d3 (6. Qe2 e6 (6... g6 7. c3
Bg7 8. d4 $16 {Here, this is very strong since White not only occupies the
centre, but also threatens e5-e6.} e5 {After this White can exploit the
weaknesses on the d-file:} 9. dxe5 Nxe5 (9... dxe5 10. c4 {[%cal Yb1c3,Yc3d5]}
(10. Rd1) (10. Bg5)) 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Bg5 O-O 12. c4 Qb6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nc3
Bg7 15. Nd5 Qe6 {Now, we can double our rooks behind the d5-knight.} 16. Rad1
Rac8 17. Rd3 $18 {White has a strategically winning position.}) (6... e5 7. c3
Be7 8. d4) {I would like to present a rare strategy, which I like very much:}
7. d3 Be7 8. Ng5 {White prepares f4. This plan works well against the line
with 4...Nxd7.} ({We can also include} 8. c4 O-O {and only then go for} 9. Ng5
h6 10. Nh3 Nb8 11. f4) 8... O-O (8... h6 9. Nh3 g5 $5) 9. f4 Ne8 ({How should
White continue after} 9... Qc7 {? I would probably play} 10. c4 {Even if Black
manages to play ...d5, after for example} Rfe8 11. Nc3 h6 12. Nf3 Bf8 13. Kh1
d5 {we are better after} 14. e5 Nh7 15. Bd2 dxc4 (15... d4 16. Ne4 $16) 16.
dxc4 $16) 10. Nf3 d5 11. c4 $1 dxc4 (11... Nc7 12. Nc3 d4 13. Nd1) 12. dxc4 Nb8
13. Rd1 Qb6 14. Nc3 Nc6 15. Be3 Nf6 16. h3 (16. Kh1) 16... Rfd8 17. e5 Ne8 18.
Ne4 Nd4 19. Nxd4 cxd4 20. Bf2 Rac8 21. b3 Rd7 22. Rd3 f5 23. exf6 Nxf6 24. Ng5
Rc6 25. Nf3 Bc5 26. Ne5 Rd8 27. Nxc6 Qxc6 28. Re1 {1-0 Glek,I-Berni,G/Lido
Estensi 2002.}) 6... e6 ({Here} 6... g6 {is playable since if White returns to
the plan c3-d4, he has lost one tempo. Still, it is White's best plan.} 7. Re1
(7. Nc3 Bg7 8. a4 O-O 9. h3 a6 (9... e5 10. Bg5) 10. Re1 Rb8 11. Bf4 Nh5 (11...
b5 12. e5 Nh5) 12. Bg5 b5 13. axb5 axb5 14. Nd5 Nhf6 15. Nxf6+ Nxf6 16. e5 dxe5
17. Nxe5 Qc7 18. Qf3) (7. Qe2 Bg7 8. c3 e5 (8... O-O 9. d4) 9. d4 {Now Black
should consider} cxd4 10. cxd4 exd4 11. Nxd4 (11. Bf4) 11... O-O 12. Nc3 Re8 {
with counterplay against e4.}) 7... Bg7 8. c3 e5 9. d4 {In spite of Black's
extra tempo, White has chances for a slight advantage.} O-O 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11.
Nxe5 (11. Bf4) 11... dxe5 12. Qe2 {Next, we play Bg5 or c4, for example} Qc7
13. c4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Yb1c3,Yc3d5]} h6 14. Nc3 Rad8 15. Be3 $16 Rd4 $2 16.
Bxd4 cxd4 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. cxd5 $18) 7. Ng5 $5 {White goes for the plan that
we already studied after 6.Qe2 e6 7.d3 Be7 8.Ng5!?} h6 8. Nh3 Be7 9. f4 Qc7 {
What should White play?} 10. c4 $1 $14 a6 11. Nc3 Rb8 12. a4 e5 $2 13. a5 (13.
Kh1 $1 {a useful move. For example} exf4 (13... O-O $2 14. f5 $1 $16 {[%cal
Yg2g4] with a strategically winning position.} ({Black gets counterplay after} 
14. g4 exf4 15. Nxf4 Ne5)) 14. Nxf4 Ne5 15. Nfd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Qd8 17. Bf4 $16)
13... O-O $6 14. f5 $18 Rfe8 15. Kh1 Nh7 16. Qf3 Qd8 17. Bd2 Ng5 18. Nxg5 Bxg5
19. Be1 Bh4 20. g3 Bf6 21. Nd5 b5 22. axb6 Nxb6 23. Ba5 Re7 24. Ra3 Reb7 25.
Rb3 Qd7 26. Rxb6 Rxb6 27. Bxb6 Qc6 28. Bc7 Rxb2 29. Nxf6+ gxf6 30. Bd8 1-0

