1. Nf3 c5 2. e4 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Nxd7 5. O-O Ngf6 6. Re1 (6. Qe2) 6...
Rc8 {This move is directed against the plan with c4.} (6... e5 $2 7. c3) (6...
g6 $2 7. c3) 7. c3 (7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 g6 $5 {Now, ...g6 is playable since
White can no longer play c3-d4.}) 7... e6 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 d5 $1 {This is
the typical reaction for Black. After passive moves, White is better:} (9...
Be7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Bf4 $14 (11. e5 $5 $14) 11... d5 12. e5 Ne8 13. Ne2 $5 {
[%cal Ge2g3,Gg3h5]}) 10. e5 Ne4 11. Nbd2 Nxd2 (11... Bb4 $2 {does not work:}
12. Nxe4 dxe4 (12... Bxe1 $2 13. Nd6+ $18) 13. Rxe4 O-O 14. Rg4 $16) 12. Qxd2
$5 {This move would not have been possible with a knight on c6 (due to ...Bb4).
White 's idea is to transfer the queen to the kinside. This manoeuvre is not
as effective as with light-squared bishops on the board, but nevertheless
offers interensting chances.} Be7 13. Qf4 O-O 14. Qg4 Re8 15. h4 $1 {An
important resource, aiming to create weaknesses in Black's position.} Qc7 16.
Bh6 g6 17. Qf4 Qc2 18. g4 $1 $16 (18. Ng5 Qf5) 18... b6 (18... Qxb2 $2 19. Rab1
Qxa2 20. Rxb7 $18) 19. b3 Ba3 20. Kg2 Qb2 21. Ng5 Re7 22. Rad1 Rc2 23. Re3 Rc3
24. h5 Qc2 25. Rxc3 Qxc3 {Now, Carlsen found the decisive combination:} 26.
Nxh7 $1 Kxh7 27. Bg5 Kg8 28. Bxe7 Bxe7 29. Rc1 $1 Qb4 30. Rc8+ Nf8 31. h6 g5
32. h7+ $1 Kg7 33. h8=Q+ $1 Kxh8 34. Qxf7 $18 Qxd4 35. Rxf8+ Bxf8 36. Qxf8+ {
The queen ending is easily winning for White.} Kh7 37. Qf7+ Kh8 38. Qh5+ Kg7
39. Qxg5+ Kh7 40. Qe7+ Kh8 41. Qf6+ Kh7 42. Qxe6 Qd1 43. Qf5+ Kg8 44. e6 1-0

