1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 5. O-O {Now we look at an example
where Black chose the right plan.} Nc6 ({or} 5... Nf6 6. Re1 Nc6 7. c3 e6) 6.
c3 Nf6 7. Re1 e6 $1 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 d5 $1 (9... Be7 $2 10. d5 (10. Nc3 $14
d5 11. e5 $16)) 10. e5 Ne4 11. Nbd2 Nxd2 (11... Bb4 $2 12. Nxe4 $18) 12. Bxd2 {
This is theoretically acceptable for Black. Yet, White has two very
interesting plan. One involves attacking chess, the other strategic chess!} Bb4
(12... Be7 13. Rc1 (13. h4 {is the slower, more strategic alternative.} O-O (
13... h5 14. Bg5) 14. h5 h6 15. Rc1 (15. Re3)) 13... O-O 14. Rc3 Rac8 (14...
Bb4 $2 {loses due to} 15. Rxc6 Bxd2 16. Rd6 $18) 15. a3 {A necessary
preparatory move.} (15. Rd3 Nb4 $132) 15... b5 16. Rd3 $1 {This "magical"
setup is scoring excellently for White although the computer assesses the
position as 0.00! White has good attacking chances and Black has to defend in
a very precise way!} h6 {This is played quite often, stopping Ng5.} (16... b4
17. Ng5 bxa3 18. bxa3 Bxg5 19. Bxg5 Ne7 20. Qh5) 17. h4 {Preparing Nh2 with
the idea of bringing the queen to g4 or h5.} b4 18. Nh2 {If Black defends with}
f5 19. exf6 Bxf6 20. Qg4 {White has play against Black's weaknesses.}) 13. Re3
{White has interesting chances after this or 13.Rc1.} (13. Rc1 Bxd2 14. Qxd2
O-O 15. h4 Rac8 16. h5 h6 17. Rc3 f5 18. exf6 Rxf6 19. Nh4 $16) 13... O-O 14.
h4 Rfc8 15. h5 Bxd2 16. Qxd2 $14 h6 17. Rc1 Ne7 18. Rec3 Rxc3 19. Rxc3 Rc8 20.
b3 b6 21. g4 a5 22. Kg2 Rc6 23. a4 Qc7 24. Rxc6 Qxc6 25. Ne1 Qc7 26. Qc2 Qd7
27. Qc3 Nc6 28. f4 Kf8 29. Nc2 Ne7 30. Ne3 g6 31. hxg6 fxg6 32. Kg3 Kf7 33. Qc2
Qc6 34. Qd2 Qd7 35. Qh2 Kg7 36. Qh4 Ng8 37. f5 exf5 38. gxf5 gxf5 39. Kf4 Qc6
40. Nxf5+ Kh7 41. Qg4 Qc1+ 42. Ne3 Qd2 43. Qd7+ Kg6 44. Qe6+ Kg7 45. Qxd5 Ne7
46. Qg2+ Qxg2 47. Nxg2 Nd5+ 48. Ke4 Nc3+ 49. Kd3 Nd5 50. Ne3 Nf4+ 51. Ke4 Ne6
52. d5 Nc5+ 53. Kf5 Nxb3 54. e6 Nc5 55. d6 b5 56. d7 Nb7 57. e7 1-0

