{[%evp 0,57,16,16,45,48,79,38,38,38,44,30,32,28,28,19,19,19,22,22,22,17,17,12,
12,11,11,10,10,9,23,4,1,4,10,-22,-13,-18,-11,-26,60,-100,-37,-60,-54,10,103,
121,410,449,577,590,29989,29990,29991,29992,29995,29996,29997,29998]} 1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 (4... Nxd7 $6 {This move is quite common
but a bit passive. This knight sould be developed to c6 in order have more
influence on important central squares. After 4...Nxd7, White usually goes for
a hedgehog setup with c4 and d4.} 5. O-O Ngf6 (5... g6 $2 6. c3 Ngf6 7. Qe2 $1
Bg7 8. d4 $16 e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 (9... dxe5 10. c4 (10. Rd1) (10. Bg5)) 10. Nxe5
dxe5 11. Bg5 O-O 12. c4 Qb6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nc3 Bg7 15. Nd5 Qe6 16. Rad1 Rac8
17. Rd3 $16) (5... e5 $2 6. c3 Ngf6 7. Re1 g6 8. d4 $16 Bg7 9. dxe5 dxe5 10.
Bg5 $16 (10. c4 $16) (10. Na3 $16)) 6. Qe2 (6. d3 $1 {THIS IS VERY INTERESTNG
IDEA !! it works only after 4...Nxd7 ....we play d3! ..and some development
moves..like Nc3 ...or c4-Nc3 ...and w soon follow with Ng5! and f4! ...with a
good version of a ....closed sicilian type of game ! ....very pleasant
positions for black !} e6 (6... g6 7. Nc3 (7. Re1 $5 Bg7 8. c3 e5 9. d4 O-O 10.
dxe5 Nxe5 11. Bf4 (11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Qe2 Qc7 13. c4 h6 14. Nc3 Rad8 15. Be3 Rd4
16. Bxd4 cxd4 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. cxd5)) (7. Qe2 Bg7 8. c3 O-O (8... e5 9. d4 cxd4
10. cxd4 exd4 11. Nxd4 (11. Bf4) 11... O-O 12. Nc3 Re8) 9. d4) 7... Bg7 8. a4 (
8. Ng5 O-O 9. f4 $14) 8... O-O 9. h3 a6 (9... e5 10. Bg5) 10. Re1 Rb8 11. Bf4
Nh5 (11... b5 12. e5 Nh5) 12. Bg5 b5 13. axb5 axb5 14. Nd5 Nhf6 15. Nxf6+ Nxf6
16. e5 dxe5 17. Nxe5 Qc7 18. Qf3) 7. Ng5 $5 {even this move right away makes
sence} (7. c4 $5 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Ne1 $5 (9. Ng5 h6 10. Nh3 Ne5 11. f4 Nc6 12.
g4 $132) 9... Ne5 10. f4 Nc6 11. g4 $1 Nd7 12. Nf3 $14) 7... h6 8. Nh3 Be7 9.
f4 Qc7 10. c4 a6 11. Nc3 Rb8 12. a4 $14 e5 13. Kh1 exf4 (13... O-O 14. f5 $16)
14. Nxf4 Ne5 15. Nfd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Qd8 17. Bf4 $16) 6... e6 $1 (6... e5 $2 7.
c3 Be7 8. d4) (6... g6 $2 7. c3 Bg7 (7... Bh6 8. d4 Bxc1 9. Rxc1 $16) 8. d4 $16
) (6... Rc8 $5 7. c4 $5 {is one more interesting move order.} (7. d4 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 g6 9. c4 Bg7 10. Rd1 O-O 11. b3 $14) (7. d3 $1 {This is also perfectly
playable!} e6 8. c4 Be7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Ne1 $1 (10. Ng5) 10... a6 11. f4 Nb8 12.
g4 $3 Nc6 13. Qg2 $14)) 7. d4 $1 (7. d3 $1 {we can still switch to the Ng5
plans !} Be7 8. Ng5 $1 (8. c4 O-O 9. Ng5 h6 10. Nh3 Nb8 11. f4 Nc6 12. Be3)
8... O-O (8... h6 9. Nh3 g5 10. f4 $16) 9. f4 Ne8 (9... Qc7 10. c4 Rfe8 11. Nc3
h6 12. Nf3 Bf8 13. Kh1 d5 14. e5 Nh7 15. Bd2 dxc4 (15... d4 16. Ne4) 16. dxc4
$16) 10. Nf3 d5 11. c4 $1 dxc4 (11... Nc7 12. Nc3 d4 13. Nd1) 12. dxc4 $16 Nb8
13. Rd1 Qb6 14. Nc3 Nc6 15. Be3 $16 {Black cannot get to d4, while White has a
big space advantage, 1-0 (28) Glek,I-Berni,G/Lido Estensi 2002.}) 7... cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Be7 (8... Rc8 9. c4 a6 10. b3 $1 {transpositions}) 9. c4 a6 10. b3 $1 {
This is the accurate move order!} ({After} 10. Nc3 Rc8 11. b3 $2 {Black has} b5
$17) 10... O-O 11. Bb2 Rc8 12. Nc3 Re8 13. Rad1 Qa5 14. Kh1 $14 {White has a
comfortable advantge. Study the MODEL GAMES to see several examples with this
setup. Both players can choose all sorts of move orders, but the main ideas
stay the same!}) 5. O-O Nf6 6. Re1 Nc6 7. c3 e6 $1 {This is Black's only good
move! In positions without the light-squared bishops where White can go for
c3-d4, plans with ...e7-e5 or ...g7-g6 are always wrong! Black must develop
with ...e6!-Be7.} (7... g6 $2 8. d4 $16 cxd4 9. cxd4 Bg7 10. d5 (10. Nc3 $16
O-O 11. d5) 10... Ne5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. f3 O-O 13. Nc3 $16 (13. Be3) (13. Qb3
$16)) (7... e5 $2 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 Be7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Bg5 $16) 8. d4 (8. d3
$5 {Caruana has played this move. The idea is to get out of book early,
develop the pieces quietly, and then try to seize the initiative in the center.
} Be7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Nf1 b5 11. d4 $132) 8... cxd4 ({Playing} 8... d5 $6 {
looks quite logical, but White has the strong continuation} 9. Ne5 $1 Qc7 {
The only move, although it may look counterintuitive since it invites Bf4.} (
9... Qc8 $2 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 (11... Qxc6 $6 12. c4 Nb6 13. d5 $18)
12. c4 Nb6 13. d5 $16) (9... Nxe5 $6 10. dxe5 Ng8 (10... Nxe4 $2 11. f3 $18)
11. exd5 Qxd5 12. Qa4+ (12. Qg4) (12. Nd2) 12... Qd7 13. Qb3 $1 $16 (13. Qxd7+
Kxd7)) 10. exd5 Nxd5 (10... Nxe5 11. Bf4 (11. dxe5 Nxd5 12. Qe2) 11... Nxd5 12.
Bxe5 Bd6 13. Qa4+ Qd7 14. Qxd7+ Kxd7 15. Bxg7 Rhg8 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. Be5 $16)
11. Nxc6 (11. Na3 $1 cxd4 12. Nb5 Qb6 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. cxd4 $14) (11. c4 Nf6
12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. d5 $14) 11... bxc6 12. c4 Nf6 13. d5 $14 cxd5 14. cxd5 O-O-O
15. Nc3 Nxd5 16. Qa4 $44 {White has more than enough compensation for the pawn.
}) 9. cxd4 d5 $1 (9... Be7 $6 10. d5 $1 $16 Ne5 11. dxe6 Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 fxe6
13. Nc3 O-O 14. Qd3 $16 (14. Qe2 $16)) 10. e5 Ne4 $1 (10... Ng8 {This may look
like a good French Defence for Black. Remember the rule for such positions:
THE KEY MOVE IS ALWAYS h4! Black will either play ...h5, giving up the g5
square he will allow us to play h4-h5! gaining space!} 11. Nc3 (11. h4 $5 Nge7
12. Nc3 $1 h5 13. Bg5 $14) 11... Nge7 12. Ne2 $1 (12. h4 $1 h5 13. Bg5 $14)
12... Ng6 (12... Nf5 13. g4 Nfe7 14. Ng3 $14) 13. h4 $1 h5 14. Nf4 Nxf4 15.
Bxf4 $14) 11. Nbd2 Nxd2 (11... Bb4 $4 12. Nxe4 $1 dxe4 (12... Bxe1 13. Nd6+)
13. Rxe4 $16 O-O 14. Rg4 $3) 12. Bxd2 {As is often the case, this position is
evaluated as equal by the computer, but there is a great number of GM games
with very good results for White! White's play is easier and we have attacking
chances! Computers can never be checkmated but humans can!} Be7 (12... Bb4 $5
13. Rc1 Bxd2 (13... O-O $4 14. Rxc6 Bxd2 15. Rd6 $18) 14. Qxd2 O-O 15. h4 $1 (
15. Re3 Rac8 16. Rec3) 15... h6 16. h5 $14) 13. Rc1 $1 (13. h4 $5 {As already
mentioned before, h4! is an important idea in these positions with pawns on
d4-e5 against pawns on d5-e6!} O-O (13... h5 $2 14. Rc1 O-O 15. Rc3 Rac8 16. a3
$16 {black will soon pay for this h5 weakness !}) 14. h5 h6 {Black should stop
h5-h6. A possible continuation:} 15. Re3 (15. Rc1) 15... Bb4 16. Rc1 Bxd2 17.
Qxd2 Rfc8 18. Rec3 Ne7 19. g4 Rxc3 20. Rxc3 Rc8 21. Ne1 Rxc3 22. Qxc3 Qc6 23.
Qxc6 (23. Qb4) 23... Nxc6 24. Nc2 Kf8 25. f4 $14 {Even in this knight endgame,
White can still press due to his space advantage on the kingside.}) 13... O-O
14. a3 (14. Rc3 $1 {I consider this to be the more accurate move order!} Rac8 {
and only now} 15. a3 b5 16. Rd3 $1) (14. h4 $5 {This is the slow stategic
strategy .}) 14... Rac8 (14... Rfc8 15. Rc3 {Our plan is Rc3-Rd3!, intending
the powerful Ng5!!. If Black plays h6 to prevent it, then we play h4! followed
by Nh2!, sacrificing the h4 pawn. Please note that WE DO NOT PLAY h5 after h4!
In this case, we need this square for our queen! Here are some sample lines
and some games - concrete theory is not needed!} Nd8 (15... b5 16. Rd3 $1 h6 (
16... a5 17. Ng5 h6 18. Nh3) 17. h4 b4 18. Nh2 $3 {I don't think that we need
to spend time on a4.} (18. a4 Na5 19. b3) 18... f5 (18... bxa3 19. bxa3 Bf8 20.
Ng4 $3 (20. Qh5 $16 Ne7 21. Bxh6 gxh6 (21... Qb5 22. Rf3 Nf5 23. Ng4 $16) 22.
Ng4 $16 Qb7 23. Nf6+ Kg7 (23... Kh8 24. Qxf7) 24. Qg4+ Ng6 25. h5 $18) 20...
Ne7 21. Bxh6 $18) 19. exf6 Bxf6 20. Qg4 $16 (20. Ng4 $5 $16 Bxh4 $2 21. Nxh6+
gxh6 22. Qg4+ Bg5 23. Bxg5 hxg5 24. Rxe6 $18) 20... bxa3 21. bxa3 h5 22. Qxh5
Nxd4 23. Bg5 Nf5 24. Bxf6 gxf6 25. Ng4 Rf8 26. Nh6+ Nxh6 27. Rg3+ Kh7 28. Rg6
Qg7 29. Rxg7+ Kxg7 30. Rxe6 Rad8 31. Re3 Ng8 32. Rg3#) 16. Rd3 Qb5 17. Bc3 $1 (
17. Bc1 $4 Rxc1) 17... a5 18. h4 $16 h6 (18... Nc6 19. Ng5 h6 20. Nh3 (20. Nxf7
Kxf7 21. Qh5+ Kg8 22. Rg3 Bf8 23. Qxh6 $13) 20... Bxh4 21. Nf4 Bg5 22. Nh5 g6
23. Nf6+ Bxf6 24. exf6) 19. Nh2 Bxh4 20. Rh3 Be7 21. Qg4 Kf8 22. Ree3 $3 $16) (
14... f6 $6 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Bf4 $3 $16 (16. Bc3 $14)) (14... Bd8 15. h4) 15.
Rc3 Nb8 (15... b5 16. Rd3 f5 (16... a5 $2 {After one mistake by Black the
attack becomes very strong! THIS is the problem for Black in this line!} 17.
Ng5 $16 Bxg5 $6 (17... b4 18. Qh5 h6 19. Nh3 $18 {[%cal Yd3g3,Yd2h6]}) 18. Bxg5
$18) 17. exf6 Rxf6 18. Qe2 $16 Bf8 19. Rc3 a6 20. Bg5 Rg6 21. h4 Bd6 22. Rec1
Bb8 23. h5 Rxg5 24. Nxg5 Bf4 25. Qc2 Bxg5 26. Rxc6 Rf8 27. Rd1 Qe8 28. Re1 Bh4
29. g3 Bf6 30. Rexe6 Qxh5 31. Rc8 Bd8 32. Rd6 Qg5 33. Qe2 h6 34. Qe6+ Kh8 35.
Rxd5 Qd2 36. Qe3 {1-0 Michalik,P (2557)-Brunner,N (2441)/Ruzomberok SVK 2014})
(15... h6 {When we see ...h6 on the board, our plan is Nh2! followed by Qg4 or
Qh5! ...and later possibly Ng4, Rg3 with sacrifces on h6 in the air!} 16. h4 $1
(16. Rd3 $1) 16... Nd8 (16... Na5 17. Rxc8 Rxc8 18. Bxa5) 17. Rd3 $14 Qb5 18.
Bc3 {With Bc3, we protect everything. On the one hand, our attack is slowed
down; on the other, Black has no more counterplay. What is the queen doing on
b5?} (18. Bc1 $4 {BE CAREFULL NOT TO FALL FOR THIS TRICK !!} Rxc1 19. Qxc1 Qxd3
$19) (18. Rb3) 18... Nc6 (18... f5 19. exf6 Bxf6 20. Rde3 $16) 19. Nh2 (19. h5)
19... Bxh4 20. Rh3 Bg5 21. Ng4 {White has a very strong attack with ideas of
Bd2 or g3-f4.}) 16. Rd3 $1 Qc6 (16... Qb5 17. Rb3 $1 (17. Bc3 $14) 17... Qc6
18. Ng5 Bxg5 19. Bxg5 Nd7 20. Qg4 f5 21. Qh4 Rfe8 22. Bf6 Nf8 23. Bxg7 Kxg7 24.
Qf6+ Kg8 25. h4 Rc7 26. Rg3+ Ng6 27. h5 Rf8 28. Qg5 Rg7 29. Rc1 Qb6 30. hxg6
Rxg6 31. Qh4 Rxg3 32. Qxg3+ Kh8 33. Qh4 Qd8 34. Qxd8 Rxd8 35. Rc7 Rg8 36. Rxb7
Rg4 37. Rxa7 Rxd4 38. b4 Rd1+ 39. Kh2 d4 40. b5 d3 41. Rd7 d2 42. a4 Kg8 43. a5
Rb1 44. b6 d1=Q 45. Rxd1 Rxd1 46. b7 {1-0 Jones,G (2654)-Gelfand,B (2777)/
London ENG 2013.}) 17. Bc3 $14 Nd7 18. h4 h6 19. Nh2 $1 {The typical idea!}
Bxh4 $2 20. Qh5 Bg5 (20... Qc4 21. Rh3 Bg5 22. Nf3 Be7 23. Re3 $40) 21. Rg3 $16
g6 $2 (21... f5 $2 22. Rxg5 hxg5 23. Nf3 $16) 22. Rxg5 $1 $18 hxg5 23. Qh6 f5
24. Qxg6+ Kh8 25. Nf3 Rce8 26. Nxg5 Re7 27. Re3 Rg7 28. Rh3+ Kg8 29. Qh6 {
1-0 Trent,L (2468)-Ninov,N (2462)/Granada ESP 2014.} *

