{I was very impressed by how McShane handled the position in this game with
the 4...Nxd7-variation!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Nxd7 5. O-O
Ngf6 6. Qe2 e6 7. d4 {White goes for the Hedgehog setup.} cxd4 8. Nxd4 a6 9. c4
Rc8 (9... Be7 10. b3) 10. b3 ({Let me repeat:} 10. Nc3 {is the wrong move
order since after} Qc7 11. b3 b5 $1 {is possible.}) 10... g6 {This has
advantages and drawbacks: the g7-bishop is generally well-placed and is
protecting the king but on the other hand the d6-pawn can get weak.} ({We have
already seen} 10... Be7 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Nc3 Qa5 13. Rad1 {[%cal Yg1h1,Yf2f4]})
11. Bb2 Bg7 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Rad1 Qc7 14. Kh1 Rfd8 15. f4 Qb8 $6 {I would
hesitate to decentralise the queen like this.} 16. Nf3 Nh5 $6 17. f5 $5 (17.
Ng5 $1 $16) 17... Re8 18. fxe6 fxe6 19. e5 Nxe5 20. Nxe5 Bxe5 21. Ne4 $1 $14
Bxb2 (21... d5 $2 22. Bxe5 Qxe5 23. Nf6+ $18) 22. Qxb2 d5 23. g4 $1 $16 dxe4
24. gxh5 {The bad position of the queen on b8 makes itself felt - Black's king
is short of defenders.} e5 25. hxg6 hxg6 26. Qg2 Rc6 27. Rd7 Rd6 28. Rdf7 Qc8
29. R7f6 Rxf6 30. Rxf6 Re7 31. Rxg6+ Kh8 32. Qg5 Qf8 33. Qh5+ Rh7 34. Qxe5+ Rg7
35. Qxg7+ Qxg7 36. Rxg7 Kxg7 37. Kg2 1-0

