{[%evp 0,29,16,16,60,60,71,38,38,38,56,56,56,36,62,31,30,32,33,34,32,26,31,30,
30,28,18,21,21,1,122,103]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Qe2 $5 {A very
rare but interesting alternative to 4.Bxd7+ - as long as we are ready to play
an endgame! ...Which is, in fact, slightly better for White, with ideas of
a4-a5! and then either Nc3 or Na3!?-Nbd2!?, when Black has played g6-Bg7. It
is an even better version for White if his king is still on e1. Sometimes, it
feels quite safe to put it on e2, being ready to activate it in the endgame
after many exchanges have occurred! Black's best moves are 4...Bxb5 and 4...
Nf6, while after 4...a6 or 4...Nc6 we can already get an advantage!} Bxb5 (4...
Nc6 $6 5. Bxc6 $1 Bxc6 (5... bxc6 6. e5 (6. c3) 6... d5 (6... Bg4 7. exd6 e6 8.
b3 $16) 7. d3 Bg4 8. Nbd2 e6 9. h3 Bh5 10. O-O Ne7 11. g4 Bg6 12. Nb3 Nc8 13.
Be3 d4 14. Bg5 Qc7 15. Nh4 $16) 6. d4 $1 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Rc8 $6 (7... Nf6 8. Nc3 (
